<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, Sept. 8, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Polls: Gore Shows Strength on Issues
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore continues to show strength on issues like
education, health care and the economy and has opened a double-digit lead among
women, new polls suggest. But the head-to-head matchup with George W. Bush
remains close. Democrat Gore and Republican Bush were virtually tied in two new
polls released today. Gore led 47 percent to 44 percent among likely voters in a
CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll. Both candidates were tied at 47 percent in an
ABC-Washington Post poll of likely voters.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Justice Dept. Studying Tire Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno said today she is looking into
whether Ford or Bridgestone/Firestone executives broke any criminal or civil
laws with their handling of complaints over tires now linked to scores of
deaths. At the same time, two senators introduced bills to force companies to
alert authorities to product safety concerns.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Philippine Hostage Release Delayed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- Negotiators delayed their departure Friday for
a southern Philippine island after new snags threatened to stop Muslim rebels
from releasing all six Europeans they are still holding. They blamed the delay
on plane problems. Earlier, however, an official close to the negotiating team
said Libyan officials had brought only $4 million in ransom money, or enough to
pay for the release of only four of the hostages. The Abu Sayyaf rebels had
earlier pledged to free all six on Friday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jury: Aryans To Pay $6.3M in Suit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COEUR D'ALENE, Idaho (AP) -- A jury today awarded $6.3 million to a woman and
her son who were attacked by Aryan Nations guards outside the white supremacist
group's north Idaho headquarters. The jury found that Aryan Nations leader
Richard Butler, the group and its corporate entity, Saphire, Inc., were
negligent in the selection, training and supervision of the security guards who
assaulted Victoria and Jason Keenan two years ago. The Keenans' attorney, Morris
Dees, had asked the jury to award more than $11 million in punitive damages.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
United Jet, Stealth Fighter in Near-Miss
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- An F-117 stealth fighter flew close enough to a United
Airlines jet to set off the passenger plane's on-board radar today, the airline
and the military said. The incident occurred shortly after United flight 174
left Los Angeles International Airport for Boston about 8:30 a.m., said Chris
Nardella, a spokeswoman for United, which is based in the Chicago suburb of Elk
Grove Village. The Boeing 757 was flying at about 10,800 feet when its on-board
radar equipment detected an approaching aircraft.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Butler: Annan Hindered U.N. Program
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan set in motion a process
in 1998 that contributed to the eventual breakdown of the U.N. weapons
inspection program, a former chief of the program said tonight. ''Did he harm
our operation? Yes,'' said Richard Butler, the Australian who once headed the
now-defunct U.N. Special Commission, known as UNSCOM. Speaking to a gathering at
the American Enterprise Institute, Butler said the turning point occurred when
Annan sent three envoys to Baghdad to discuss the Security Council resolutions
on Iraq that were passed after the Persian Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
MTV Awards: Eminem Vs. 'N Sync
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A mooning, profane jokes that tested the censor's trigger
finger and a winner who admitted she hated making videos -- MTV's annual Video
Music Awards lived up to a reputation for unpredictability tonight. Along the
way, profane rapper Eminem -- the subject of a pre-show protest over his violent
lyrics -- won best male video for ''The Real Slim Shady.'' He was nominated for
six awards overall.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose early Friday, buoyed by strength in U.S.
technology shares in New York. The dollar was lower against the yen. The
benchmark 225-issue Nikkei gained 153.39 points, or 0.94 percent, to 16,453.85
in the first hour of trading. In New York, the Nasdaq composite index rose 85.01
points today to close at 4,085.35. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 50.77
points to end at 11,259.87.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mariners Beat Blue Jays 8-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Freddy Garcia allowed two singles in eight scoreless innings
as Seattle defeated the Toronto Blue Jays 8-1 tonight, only the Mariners'
seventh win in 24 games. Mark McLemore drove in three runs and Al Martin homered
for the AL West leaders.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by KRISTEN DE GROOT
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
