<DOCNO> APW20000908.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast Negotiators To Resume Talks  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN LAUB
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- With an eye on the calendar, President
Clinton sent Israeli and Palestinian negotiators back to work after
they failed to reach agreement on how to share Jerusalem holy sites
despite his personal intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Pessimism prevailed, however. U.S. officials said only a few
weeks remained to secure a treaty, and the second-tier negotiators
who are to reconvene in the coming days in the Middle East have not
scored many achievements in the past.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Clinton's mediation effort during this week's
U.N. Millennium Summit was the fate of a 36-acre walled compound in
Jerusalem's Old City. It is revered by Jews as the Temple Mount,
the site of their former Temples, and by Muslims as Haram
as-Sharif, or Noble Sanctuary, with two mosques marking the spot
where the Prophet Mohammed ascended to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has proposed complex sovereignty arrangements
to accommodate rival Israeli and Palestinian claims, including
placing some areas under divine sovereignty to enable both sides to
save face in accepting the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Thursday he was willing
to contemplate U.S. ideas, provided Arafat was willing to
reciprocate.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said no Israeli prime minister would ever accept
Palestinian sovereignty over the Temple Mount -- ''a cornerstone of
our identity'' -- but suggested he would not necessarily insist on
full Israeli control over the sacred compound.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, in turn, said anything less than full Palestinian
sovereignty over all of traditionally Arab east Jerusalem,
including the Old City and its Muslim and Christian holy sites, was
out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't betray my people. I can't betray the Arabs. I can't
betray the Christians. I can't betray the Muslims,'' Arafat told
CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, for the first time, revealed specifics of a U.S. proposal
made at the Mideast summit in July at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   At the U.S. presidential retreat, he said, Clinton suggested
either postponing agreement on all of Jerusalem by one or two
years, or on the Old City by 15 years, while trying to reach an
accord on the remaining issues such as borders of a Palestinian
state and the fate of millions of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ''After quite painful hesitation, we were ready to say that we
are ready to contemplate it,'' Barak said, adding that the
Palestinians rejected the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat bristled at accusations that he was to blame for the
deadlock, saying he was holding out for the legitimate rights of
his people.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Nabil Shaath said he felt it had been a
mistake to focus on the hardest dispute, over the holy sites.
Negotiators will now try to make progress on the other issues, such
as land, refugees and borders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we finish four out of five (issues), we will go armed with
this success,'' he said. ''Isn't it much better than leaving
everything to failure?''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said both sides promised
to work hard, adding that Clinton would be available to the
negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the truth is, just look at the calendar,'' she said.
''There is not a lot of time. And I think we are talking about the
fact that there are a relative number of weeks here.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak noted that the U.S. Congress, which would have to approve
billions of dollars in funding for a peace treaty, will adjourn in
early October.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli leader faces his own deadline. The Israeli
parliament, increasingly hostile to Barak's peace policies,
reconvenes at the end of October -- and may have enough votes by
then to topple him.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat was to leave Friday for the Gaza Strip to lead a PLO
meeting that will decide whether to proclaim a state on Wednesday,
the deadline for a peace treaty, or set a new date.
</P>
<P>
   A postponement is likely, since Arafat has been cautioned by
many world leaders at the U.N. summit that unilateral steps would
harm peace prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said Arafat should expect to get a worse deal, not a
better one, by playing for time. ''I don't believe President
Clinton or the Israeli government will be able to negotiate under
the same terms two months from now,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-08-00 0102 </TRAILER>
