<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Fuel Protest Widening  </HEADLINE>
By ANGELA DOLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Throughout France, a crippling nationwide protest
over high fuel prices is forcing drivers to go to extremes for
gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   At a Shell station in Paris on Thursday, businessman Louis
Chevalier filled two plastic containers with gas, a favor for a
colleague visiting from the central city of Tours, where it is
scarce.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's taking them back with him on the train tonight,''
Chevalier said.
</P>
<P>
   The protest by French truckers was entering its fifth day
Friday. After they sealed off the roads to nearly 100 of the
country's oil refineries and fuel depots, many gas stations were
forced to hang ''empty'' signs.
</P>
<P>
   Senior government ministers, hoping to keep the movement from
snowballing, warned protesters to end their blockades before they
hurt France's newly healthy economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we let things go on, that could break the process of growth
and development that's going on in our country,'' Transport
Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot told RTL radio.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations began quietly in August, with fishermen
blocking a few ports to protest rising fuel costs. After the
government offered them financial help, truckers began calling for
attention, and farmers and taxi drivers added their voices to the
protests.
</P>
<P>
   In northern France on Thursday, farmers in more than 50 tractors
blocked all freight access to the Channel Tunnel, preventing trucks
from boarding trains to Britain, said Vincent Fournier, an activist
with the FNSEA union.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, about 150 farmers and truck drivers protesting the
high cost of fuel blockaded the entrance to a Shell Oil refinery in
northwest England early Friday. They refused to let trucks pass
into or out of the refinery at Ellesmere Port, south of Liverpool.
</P>
<P>
   The French government had offered to give truckers a 5-cent
reimbursement per liter of fuel this year, and a 3.5-cent refund
per liter on gasoline taxes next year.
</P>
<P>
   After most truckers rejected the offer Wednesday, Socialist
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said the government would go ''no
further'' and ruled out future negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac, in New York at the U.N. Millennium
Summit, called Thursday for a rapid end to the protests and said
oil-producing nations should be aware of the harm that high prices
can cause.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are aware there's a problem,'' he said. ''It's world
growth that is at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   World oil prices have more than tripled since hitting a 12-year
low of less than $11 a barrel in December 1998, before the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries slashed production to
force prices higher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-08-00 0125 </TRAILER>
