<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, Sept. 8, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mideast Negotiators To Resume Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- With an eye on the calendar, President Clinton sent
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators back to work after they failed to reach
agreement on how to share Jerusalem holy sites despite his personal
intervention. Pessimism prevailed, however. U.S. officials said only a few weeks
remained to secure a treaty, and the second-tier negotiators who are to
reconvene in the coming days in the Middle East have not scored many
achievements in the past. The United States has proposed complex sovereignty
arrangements to accommodate rival Israeli and Palestinian claims, including
placing some areas under divine sovereignty to enable both sides to save face in
accepting the compromise.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Atlantis Fueled For Morning Liftoff
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Atlantis was fueled early Friday
for liftoff on a mission to furnish the growing international space station.
Forecasters said rain and low clouds could scuttle the 8:45 a.m. launch. Because
of the extremely short launch window -- just a few minutes -- the weather had to
be good from the outset. Atlantis' 11-day voyage will be the first shuttle
flight in almost four months and the start of what NASA hopes will be a
rapid-fire series of missions to the space station. The seven astronauts and
cosmonauts will be the first to float into the space station's new Russian-made
control module, Zvezda.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Polls: Gore Shows Strength on Issues
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore continues to show strength on issues like
education, health care and the economy and has opened a double-digit lead among
women, new polls suggest. But the head-to-head matchup with George W. Bush
remains close. Democrat Gore and Republican Bush were virtually tied in two new
polls released today. Gore led 47 percent to 44 percent among likely voters in a
CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll. Both candidates were tied at 47 percent in an
ABC-Washington Post poll of likely voters.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Files Complaint Vs Mitsubishi
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The government on Friday filed a criminal complaint against
Mitsubishi Motors Inc., Japan's fourth-largest automaker, for covering up
defects for more than 20 years. Shortly after the government action, Mitsubishi
President Katsuhiko Kawasoe announced his intention to resign to take
responsibility for the scandal. Kawasoe's announcement came just hours before
Tokyo-based Mitsubishi was expected to announce a major management reshuffle as
part of a plan to repair its badly-damaged image.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Justice Dept. Studying Tire Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno said today she is looking into
whether Ford or Bridgestone/Firestone executives broke any criminal or civil
laws with their handling of complaints over tires now linked to scores of
deaths. At the same time, two senators introduced bills to force companies to
alert authorities to product safety concerns.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
United Jet, Stealth Fighter in Near-Miss
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- An F-117 stealth fighter flew close enough to a United
Airlines jet to set off the passenger plane's on-board radar today, the airline
and the military said. The incident occurred shortly after United flight 174
left Los Angeles International Airport for Boston about 8:30 a.m., said Chris
Nardella, a spokeswoman for United, which is based in the Chicago suburb of Elk
Grove Village. The Boeing 757 was flying at about 10,800 feet when its on-board
radar equipment detected an approaching aircraft.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
MTV Awards: Eminem Vs. 'N Sync
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A mooning, profane jokes that tested the censor's trigger
finger and a winner who admitted she hated making videos -- MTV's annual Video
Music Awards lived up to a reputation for unpredictability tonight. Along the
way, profane rapper Eminem -- the subject of a pre-show protest over his violent
lyrics -- won best male video for ''The Real Slim Shady.'' He was nominated for
six awards overall.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei gained 153.39 points, or 0.94
percent, to 16,453.85 in the first hour of trading. In New York, the Nasdaq
composite index rose 85.01 points today to close at 4,085.35. The Dow Jones
industrial average fell 50.77 points to end at 11,259.87.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nigerian Runner Killed in Acident
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- A Nigerian runner who had been training with his
nation's Olympic team was struck by a car and killed Thursday night in
southwestern Sydney. Hyginus Anugo, 22, a promising 200- and 400-meter runner
who had participated in the World Junior Championships in 1996 in Sydney, was
hit as he crossed a street, the official Olympic News Service said.
</P>
