<DOCNO> APW20000908.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 02:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman Eyes Bush Health Care  </HEADLINE>
By BRIGITTE GREENBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Joseph Lieberman, who says he's a ''truth
teller,'' not an ''attack dog'' critic of the Republicans, came to
George W. Bush's Texas to raise anew the Democrats' contention that
Bush has failed to provide health care for millions of children.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bush's running mate, former Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney laid his own campaign plans for Lieberman's home state of
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, the Connecticut senator and vice presidential running
mate of Al Gore, planned to meet Friday in Houston with Texas
families, some of whom have struggled to get health care services
for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking aboard his plane en route to Houston, Lieberman said:
''We're going to talk about children's health care and particularly
about our plan'' to extend health insurance to all children by the
year 2005. Asked whether he would point out that some 1.4 million
Texas children lack health insurance, he said, ''It's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has said repeatedly that he sees himself not so much
in the ''attack dog'' role traditionally taken by some vice
presidential candidates as in the role of ''truth teller.''
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge recently ordered Texas to improve its Medicaid
program, ruling that too many low-income families were not getting
the care they need despite a 1996 agreement in which the state
promised to make major improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Texas governor, has said his government is performing
well on the matter and that the court order was the work of a
liberal, activist judge.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee this week began airing
television commercials pointing to the federal court order and
saying, ''Bush's record: It's becoming an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman planned to return to Texas on Monday with stops in
Austin and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, in turn, was to campaign Friday in the senator's home
state, appearing at a senior citizens community in Shelton to talk
about Medicare and prescription drug coverage. Later, Cheney was
attending a Republican fund-raiser in Greenwich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
