<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barges, Farmers Win River Battle  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Though President Clinton awaits with a
threatened veto, barge and farming interests have won the latest
round in their battle with environmentalists over water levels in
the Missouri River.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted 52-45 Thursday to retain legislative language
that blocks federal agencies from allowing a springtime surge in
the river's flow to save endangered shorebirds and fish. The
restriction has been enacted each of the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   With their vote, senators rejected an effort led by Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., that would have allowed the
extra water into the 2,500-mile waterway.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe people, property and fish can all be protected at
the same time without increasing the risk of flooding,'' said Sen.
Kit Bond, R-Mo., the author of the restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The provision was included in a $22.5 billion measure financing
energy and water programs for the coming fiscal year. The overall
bill was approved 93-1, more than two months after the House
approved a similar version. Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., cast the only
''no'' vote.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's passage was a rare bit of progress as Congress
struggled to complete its budget work for fiscal 2001, which begins
Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of the 13 annual spending bills that finance government
agencies remain incomplete, and eight -- including the energy and
water measure -- face administration veto threats. House Republican
leaders had hoped to approve three of the measures on Thursday --
covering the Treasury, Congress and the District of Columbia -- but
didn't even try in the face of likely defeats.
</P>
<P>
   The Army Corps of Engineers is months away from revising its
''master manual'' for managing Missouri River dams and is working
with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service to restore habitat for
three threatened and endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   The wildlife agency wants to release more water starting next
year at Gavins Point Dam on the border between Nebraska and South
Dakota, a change intended to replicate the natural flow of the
river before it was dammed for navigation.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers worry about an increased risk of flooding and say that
at the very least, the spring rise would keep their fields too wet
to plant. And the navigation industry says the plan's call for low
midsummer waters would shut down traffic from barges carrying
steel, fertilizer, construction materials and other cargo during
critical summer months.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said outdated river management policies favor the $7
million barge industry downstream, but threaten a $90 million
upstream recreation industry -- not to mention the least tern,
piping plover and pallid sturgeon.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly, this rider is designed to protect special downstream
financial interests and to stop effective management of the
river,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   The overall bill is nearly $1.3 billion above this year's levels
and is loaded with water and energy projects for every state. But
while it adds $400 million to Clinton's $13.5 billion request for
defense programs like nuclear weapons testing, it trims $600
million from his $9 billion proposal for domestic programs, such as
energy research.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is for Senate-House bargainers to write a
compromise bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-08-00 0245 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000908.0029 </DOCNO>
