<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 02:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pipeline Safety Bill Passes Senate  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN HUGHES
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pipeline workers who reveal safety problems
would receive whistleblower protection under a Senate-passed bill
that also would increase fines, boost state oversight and require
operators to disclose more information about their pipes.
</P>
<P>
   The bill by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., which passed Thursday
without objection, also increases funding for the federal agency
that oversees pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., said ''there is no doubt'' that an
Aug. 19 natural gas pipeline explosion in Carlsbad, N.M. -- which
left 12 dead -- created momentum to pass the bill this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''People in communities through which pipelines go (will) know
what is going on and have some say,'' said Sen. Slade Gorton,
R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would require pipeline operators for the first time to
submit detailed plans to the federal Office of Pipeline Safety
showing that the operators had conducted tests and inspections and
taken other steps to make the lines safe.
</P>
<P>
   The operators also would be required to show the Transportation
Department agency that they have trained employees operating the
pipes. Fines for safety violators would be increased from $500,000
to $1 million, and federal funding for the Office of Pipeline
Safety would increase by $13 million annually by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, Gorton and McCain have been pushing to pass tougher
pipeline safety legislation after a Bellingham, Wash., gasoline
pipeline rupture and explosion last year left three people dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Commerce Committee approved McCain's bill in June,
but the measure stalled for weeks, largely due to criticisms of the
bill by the natural gas industry officials, Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   She said industry officials realized they had a public relations
problem following the New Mexico disaster and relented on some of
their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   But an industry official said the accident did not play a role.
</P>
<P>
   Gay Friedmann, senior vice president of legislative affairs for
the Interstate Natural Gas Association of America, said it took
time for all the parties involved in talks over the bill to reach
an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think it's a tough bill,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But critics said penalties in the bill are still too weak and
that the Office of Pipeline Safety should not be left to enforce
the penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Other provisions of the bill would:
</P>
<P>
   --Require operators to report spills of 5 gallons or more, rather
than the current requirement of more than 200 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   --Allow states -- with Office of Pipeline Safety permission -- to
investigate pipeline accidents and examine new pipeline
construction.
</P>
<P>
   --Require operators to make available to the public maps,
emergency response plans and spill incident reports.
</P>
<P>
   Several House pipeline safety bills have been introduced, but
House Transportation Committee Chairman Bud Shuster, R-Pa., is
crafting a new bill similar to McCain's version that a
Transportation subcommittee is expected to take up as early as next
week.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The bill is S. 2438.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Web site http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-08-00 0246 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000908.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 04:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MTV Awards Security Was Tight  </HEADLINE>
By ALY SUJO
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- While a gathering of world leaders kept
authorities on alert on Manhattan's East Side, a gathering of rock
stars in midtown created a whole new set of security jitters.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers and rock's private armies of bodyguards were out
in force to keep the peace at MTV's Video Music Awards Thursday
night as the second day of the United Nations Millennium Summit
wound down.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Radio City Music Hall, hundreds of New York Police
Department officers kept watch over fans standing six-deep on the
sidewalks. Top-selling acts such as Britney Spears, boy band 'N
Sync and foul-mouthed rapper Eminem relied on their own keepers for
protection.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the night, at least five men in the crowd had been
arrested, charged with sexually abusing women.
</P>
<P>
   One bodyguard for the band Rage Against the Machine tried in
vain to shield an unruly band member from police and was himself
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Bassist Timmy Commerford, who disrupted the show by dangling for
several minutes above the stage, was hustled outside by a phalanx
of plainclothes officers, pushed against a limousine, and
handcuffed. He was charged with assault and resisting arrest,
according to New York Police Detective Ed Reuss. His bodyguard,
Perrin Bentle, was arrested for obstructing justice.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're hurting me, man. You don't have to hurt me,''
Commerford shouted as he was taken away, his shirt in tatters.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Durst, lead singer for the rap-metal band Limp Bizkit,
which was accepting an award for best rock video at the time, said
the arrest was ''well-deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He was freaking out,'' Durst said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Zimet, head of security for MTV, said earlier there was
concern about possible disturbances during the broadcast after
members of the Gay and Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation promised
a protest against the network. The organization has criticized the
network's support of Eminem, saying his lyrics promote violence
against homosexuals and women.
</P>
<P>
   ''We heard that (gay and lesbian rights group) GLAAD might be
showing up to protest, so we're doing everything we can to keep
things moving peacefully. We're particularly concerned that
something might happen,'' Zimet said.
</P>
<P>
   In the crowd outside, two men and three teen-age boys were
charged in separate incidents with sexually abusing six women.
Police said that in all of the cases, the suspects rubbed up
against the women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-08-00 0431 </TRAILER>
