<HEADLINE> UK Detectives in China for DNA  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Three British detectives are taking DNA samples
in southeast China in hopes of identifying 58 illegal immigrants
found suffocated in the back of a truck in England.
</P>
<P>
   The samples will be taken from presumed relatives of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives, who traveled to Fujian province after arriving
in Beijing on Tuesday, will work with Chinese authorities during
their investigation, the official China Daily said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives' mission is part of efforts by Chinese and
British authorities to identify the 58 Chinese found dead in June
in the back of a truck carrying tomatoes from Zeebrugge, Belgium,
to Dover, on the southern English coast.
</P>
<P>
   Many if not all of the victims were believed to have come from
areas around Fuqing and Changle cities in Fujian, the China Daily
said.
</P>
<P>
   The coastal province, where the illicit trade in people
smuggling is based, has tightened border controls since the truck
deaths and intensified crackdowns on the smugglers, known as
snakeheads, who charge up to $60,000 to spirit illegal immigrants
abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
