<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Congress Lifts Immunity  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE NORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Argentina's Senate approved a
measure Friday that strips lawmakers of their immunity from
criminal investigation -- a move prompted by the outcry over a
vote-buying scandal that has implicated 11 senators.
</P>
<P>
   The bill will become law if it is signed by President Fernando
De la Rua. But it doesn't mean lawmakers will be subject to arrest
or prosecution for wrongdoing: While the measure lets
investigations of legislators proceed, it leaves the rest of their
immunity intact.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, with only two senators opposing, came a day after the
lower house approved the bill. Previously, it had languished in
Congress for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's swift approval was seen as a clear sign that the Senate
wants to rebuild its image. Lawmakers began their drive to push the
bill through after the bribery scandal erupted last week.
</P>
<P>
   A federal probe has been launched into accusations that several
senators took bribes in return for supporting a controversial labor
reform bill passed by the Senate last April. The investigator,
federal judge Carlos Liporaci, has named 11 senators as being
implicated.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, the Senate approved a keynote economic bill
aimed at lifting Argentina out of a 16-month-long recession.
</P>
<P>
   The bill aims to assuage investors' concerns over Argentina's
short-term financial position, giving increased powers to the
executive branch in the event of a financial emergency. However,
the Senate introduced amendments that watered down the bill
considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Economy Minister Jose Luis Machinea had appealed to Senate not
to make the changes, saying they would ''drastically reduce''
Argentina's financial capacity in a time of crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-08-00 1404 </TRAILER>
