<HEADLINE> Chinese Ship Finds N. Koreans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A Chinese ship towed more than 100 North Koreans
aboard a barge back to North Korea after it found them drifting at
sea, China's state news agency said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Crew members of the Chinese ship, the Zhehai 314, spotted the
motorless, flat-bottomed barge on Thursday as it drifted about 54
miles south of Dandong port, near the North Korean border, Xinhua
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Its passengers told Chinese crew members that their vessel was
being pulled by a tugboat on Monday when the tow line snapped. They
were waving their clothes to draw attention, the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese vessels towed the barge into North Korean waters after
failing in attempts to contact that country's maritime authorities,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The Xinhua report did not say where the barge had been headed or
describe the health of the passengers, who had spent four days
adrift.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of North Koreans live illegally in China. Many
fled food shortages and tough living conditions back home.
</P>
