<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan: Immigrants Back to China  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan took a small step toward opening
direct transportation links with rival China on Friday, putting 115
illegal Chinese immigrants in boats and returning them to the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan frequently returns stowaways and other illegal immigrants
to China by allowing Chinese boats to pick them up on Taiwan's
outlying islands and ferry them back to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday's repatriation was the first time Taiwanese boats
took the mainlanders on the two-hour trip to China. The boats left
the island of Matsu and sailed to the southeastern Chinese province
of Fujian.
</P>
<P>
   Liu Teh-shun of Taiwan's Mainland Affairs Council, which handles
Taiwan's China policy, said those being returned were legally
employed by Taiwanese fishing boats but didn't have the required
documents to be on Taiwanese land. He said it was a special case
and that future repatriations would not necessarily be conducted
the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ''It all depends on future situations,'' Liu said.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan has banned direct air and shipping links with China since
the Communist Party took over the mainland in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of direct transportation links, business
between the two sides is booming, with Taiwanese investing as much
as $40 billion since they were allowed to enter the mainland market
in the 1980s. Much of the trade flows through Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Many Taiwanese businesses are clamoring for the transportation
ban to be lifted, and newly elected Taiwanese President Chen
Shui-bian has pledged to study the issue seriously. However,
political tensions remain high between the two sides, and there is
no timetable for ending the ban.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-08-00 1405 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
