<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall on Earnings Warnings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip and technology stocks fell Friday as
investors, reacting to a series of earnings warnings, decided to
take profits from the market's recent rally.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 41.81 at 11,218.06.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was down 70.77 at 4,027.58. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 6.05 to 1,496.46.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we're doing now is pricing in some measure of an economic
slowdown. We're looking at a fair number of warnings about
slowdowns in the third quarter,'' said Chris Dickerson, an analyst
with Global Market Strategists in Gainesville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Before the market opened, a handful of companies warned that
their earnings would not meet expectations.
</P>
<P>
   A warning from Gadzoox Networks pushed its shares down $1.88 --
or more than 18 percent -- to $8.44 on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Automotive parts maker TRW's stock fell nearly 10 percent early
in the day on its warning of disappointing results, but, by
afternoon, its shares had inched back up to $44.50, only 75 cents
off its closing price Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of First Data dropped $3.94 to $39.75, a 9 percent change
after an analyst downgraded the credit-card transaction processor's
stock to ''outperform'' from ''strong buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson, the Global Market Strategists analyst, said the
market's focus on tech stocks one day, then blue chips another
reflects its lack of direction -- a listlessness which makes life
difficult for investors and money managers.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq surged Thursday, while the Dow fell 50.77 after
chemical company DuPont warned that its earnings would be down
because of soft demand and increased costs. Earlier in the week,
investors had bid blue chips higher.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anytime anything looks to be moving, money mangers jump into
that sector because they have to squeeze out what percentage of
profit they can. They'll jump in for a couple of days and then jump
out,'' he said. ''There's a rush almost to avoid not losing out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 3.79 at 539.03.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by about a 6-to-5 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 650.25 million
shares, compared to 655.49 million the previous session.
</P>
<P>
