<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Widow of Slain Premier Slams Barak  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Assassinated Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin would
never have offered Palestinians control over parts of the Old City
of Jerusalem, as Ehud Barak has done, Rabin's widow said in remarks
published Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yitzhak is spinning in his grave,'' Leah Rabin told the Yediot
Ahronot daily.
</P>
<P>
   Rabin started the peace process with the Palestinians. His
widow's remarks were likely to inspire Israeli hard-liners, who
oppose Prime Minister Barak's proposed concessions to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said in response: ''I respect her.''
</P>
<P>
   ''More than once I have asked myself how Yitzhak would have
acted in these situations,'' Barak told public television. ''He was
the man who brought me into political life. I am convinced that I
am doing the correct things for the state of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabin was gunned down in 1995 by an opponent of his peace
policies after he became the first Israeli premier to shake the
hand of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, reviled as a terrorist
until he signed an interim peace accord with Rabin's government in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has reportedly offered Arafat sovereignty in Arab
neighborhoods and control of Muslim holy sites in Jerusalem, while
Israel would have sovereignty on the Temple Mount, where the
biblical Jewish Temples stood.
</P>
<P>
   The hill, known to Muslims as Haram as-Sharif, the Noble
Sanctuary, is the site of the Islamic Dome of the Rock shrine and
the Al-Aqsa mosque. Arafat demands full Palestinian sovereignty
there. Peace talks are stalemated over the issue, which caused the
failure of a July summit between Arafat and Barak in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Leah Rabin said concessions in Jerusalem were a taboo for her
husband, who fought in the 1948 war that followed Israel's creation
and watched as Israeli forces lost the Old City and its Jewish
residents were taken captive.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was thankful that in 1967 he was the army chief of staff
who liberated it,'' she said. Israel captured the Old City, along
with the West Bank and Gaza Strip, in the 1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is in New York attending the U.N. Millennium Summit.
President Clinton met separately with Barak and Arafat but
apparently failed to achieve a breakthrough in the stalled talks.
</P>
<P>
   Leah Rabin criticized the way Barak is handling the
negotiations. She said Barak should not have gone into crucial
talks with Arafat before repairing the personal relationship
between the two leaders, which she said had been strained for
months.
</P>
<P>
   She said the peace process Rabin started was designed to build
trust and good will, but that has not happened. Despite Barak's
claims, she said, he is not Rabin's spiritual successor.
</P>
<P>
   ''He would not have made concessions on the Temple Mount and the
Old City,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Leah Rabin ridiculed Arafat's reported offer of Israeli
sovereignty over the Jewish Quarter in the Old City, while the
Palestinians rule the rest of Jerusalem, including Muslim,
Christian and Jewish holy sites. ''They are prepared to let us pray
at the Western Wall. Isn't that beyond belief?'' she scoffed.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Wall is the last remnant of the biblical Temple
Mount. Most rabbis ban Jews from entering the Temple Mount because
of its holiness, and the Western Wall below has become Judaism's
holiest site for prayer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
