<HEADLINE> Fujimori dodges questions on Berenson; justice minister says case for courts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) - Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori on
Friday dodged reporters' questions about the case of jailed New
Yorker Lori Berenson; his justice minister maintained it was a
matter for the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot in advance anticipate a judgment,'' Justice Minister
Albert Bustamante said at a news conference that Fujimori held on
the sidelines of U.N. Millennium Summit. ''We belong to the
executive, not to the judicial branch of power.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a possibility of being condemned and (a possibility)
of being freed,'' Bustamante added.
</P>
<P>
   Berenson, 30, was convicted of treason by a military tribunal in
1996 for allegedly helping a rebel group, the Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Movement, plot an attack on the Peruvian Congress.
She denies the charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Peruvian government recently revoked a life sentence handed
down by a military court of hooded judges and granted Berenson a
new, civilian trial.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori said at the time that Berenson's sentence was
overturned because of new evidence showing Berenson was not a
leader of the rebel group as she was charged when convicted of
treason four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Peruvian president on Friday told reporters that the
nation's constitution requires a military trial for people arrested
of terrorist violence or of being leaders of terrorist
organizations. Civilian courts handle ''simple terrorism,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Berenson's case is now being examined and prepared by a
prosecutor and a judge in closed-door hearings. Once the evidence
and witness testimonies have been collected and reviewed, a higher
prosecutor will formally charge Berenson. She will then appear in
an open trial before a three-judge panel.
</P>
<P>
   A conviction of terrorism by a civilian court carries a minimum
20-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Berenson's parents, Mark and Rhoda Berenson of Manhattan, have
worked ceaselessly to demonstrate their daughter was a journalist,
not a terrorist, and to condemn harsh conditions she has lived
under in Peruvian prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Berenson, 30, a former Massachusetts Institute of Technology
student, arrived in Peru in 1994 as an accredited reporter for a
pair of liberal-leaning U.S. magazines, Third World Report and
Modern Times.
</P>
<P>
   Peruvian authorities charged that she used the press credentials
as a ruse to interview members of Congress, while her real motive
was providing a blueprint of the building. They describe her as a
frustrated radical who came to Peru in search of a revolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
