<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N.: Fighting in Sierra Leone  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Gunbattles erupted this week
between rival factions in Sierra Leone, U.N. officials said Friday,
raising fears for the safety of six British soldiers held hostage
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Jordanian U.N. peacekeepers witnessed several hours of gunfire
Wednesday between members of the West Side Boys, a renegade
military gang that is holding the captives, and a ragtag
pro-government militia of traditional hunters, U.N. spokeswoman
Hirut Befecadu said.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred along a road in Magbeni, a village about
45 miles east of the capital, Freetown, Befecadu said. The fighting
has since died down although armed U.N. convoys were escorting all
civilians moving through the area, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The village is close to where the West Side Boys captured 11
British soldiers and a Sierra Leonean soldier on Aug. 25. Five
British officers were freed last week.
</P>
<P>
   British army spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Tony Cramp said negotiators
feared that clashes between the skirmishing factions could
jeopardize ''the safety of our soldiers still in captivity.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Cramp said British officials remain committed to talks
with the captors and said the two sides were in regular contact. On
several occasions, officials have spoken with the hostages, who
they said remained in good spirits.
</P>
<P>
   The West Side Boys are a notoriously undisciplined gang that has
fought both the Sierra Leone government and the country's brutal
rebel Revolutionary United Front.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, several dozen British paratroopers arrived in
Sierra Leone from Dakar, Senegal, to give negotiators the option of
a military rescue.
</P>
<P>
   The British hostages, members of the 1st Irish Regiment, were
stationed at Benguema, about 25 miles east of Freetown, where
British instructors were training Sierra Leonean army recruits.
</P>
<P>
   The captured men's colleagues were being returned to Britain
this week, and 220 others from the regiment were being flown in to
replace them.
</P>
<P>
   They are retraining Sierra Leone's shattered defense force to
fight the rebels, who are responsible for the deaths and
intentional mutilation of tens of thousands of civilians since war
began in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year after signing a July 1999 peace accord, the
Revolutionary United Front rebels renewed Sierra Leone's war in May
by seizing hundreds of U.N. peacekeepers and attacking towns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-08-00 1541 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000908.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A flotilla of experts to discuss vitality of world's canals  </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - It's almost like being transported into
the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   The meandering trail is a man-made ribbon of water. Fields,
forests and quaint villages roll gently into view. In place of the
clip-clop of a mule, there's the soothing, putt-putt rhythm of a
boat engine.
</P>
<P>
   Cruising the Erie Canal is clearly Tom Grasso's favorite way to
get across New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's relaxing, it's calming, it's just fun,'' the retired
geologist said. ''The scenery is gorgeous, the history is
spectacular. You can't say enough about how hectic our lives are,
but on the canal it's like the other end of the extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Grasso acknowledged, ''one of the appeals of canaling
is there's not a lot of people interested in it. There's not a long
line anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the irony.
</P>
<P>
   As president of the Canal Society of New York, Grasso's mission
is to turn the state's 525-mile Barge Canal system into a
recreational hotspot - or at least something more akin to the
highly traversed, artificially created waterways of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   He's hoping to pick up a few dynamic ideas about canal
revitalization at the six-day World Canals Conference, which opens
here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 300 canal experts and enthusiasts in attendance will
be historians, entrepreneurs and government officials from as far
away as Britain, France and the Czech Republic. Greeting the
visitors will be a flotilla of as many as 100 boats that will
congregate along the Genesee River after heading north into the
city from the Erie Canal.
</P>
<P>
   The 175-year-old canal carried a million settlers into the
nation's heartland and created a cheap route for hauling lumber,
wheat, stone and other cargo. It transformed New York into
America's first boom state before being largely eclipsed by trains,
trucks and the St. Lawrence Seaway up north, which opened up the
Great Lakes to oceangoing vessels.
</P>
<P>
   About 15,000 tons of freight are still carried each year across
the entire New York network, which includes the Champlain, Oswego
and Cayuga-Seneca canals. But the focus has shifted to luring
recreational traffic since the Transportation Department turned the
reins over to the New York State Thruway, the waterway's proprietor
for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a weeklong vacation on a canal, not altogether unusual in
places like Ireland, Belgium and France, is still ''a bit foreign''
to most Americans, said Kristen Hanifin of the New York State Canal
Corp., a Thruway subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   And so progress is coming slowly. The Thruway said nearly
142,000 pleasure craft passed through locks on the entire canal
system last year, up from 132,000 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   With federal and state funds pouring into renovating the canal
system and its surroundings in recent years, Hanifin thinks U.S.
canal cruises will inevitably become more popular. ''People these
days are always looking for something a little bit unique,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: New York State Canal Corp., www.canals.state.ny.us
or call 1-800-4-CANAL4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
