<HEADLINE> Putin: Oil Fields Will Pump Again  </HEADLINE>
By GERALD NADLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin showed his
support at the signing Friday of a U.S.-backed $292 million loan
package to revitalize part of Siberia's giant Samotlor oil field.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who was in New York for the U.N. Millennium Summit of
world leaders, came to the signing of the agreement at Russia's
U.N. mission after meeting Cuban President Fidel Castro there.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year loans, guaranteed by the Export Import Bank of the
United States, will let the Tyumen Oil Company of Russia buy oil
equipment and services from the Dallas-based Halliburton Co.,
formerly run by Republican vice presidential candidate Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Samotlor is Russia's biggest oil field, but it is in need of
vital repairs. The field is now waterlogged, after it was flooded
in the Soviet era when workers pumped in water in an attempt to get
the oil out quickly -- a shortsighted policy that ruins the oil
wells.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like to congratulate you and wish you all the best,''
Putin told the gathering of officials and bank and oil executives.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Kukes, president and chief executive officer of Tyumen
Oil, said Putin's presence at the signing was ''a clear signal for
the business and investment communities in the West that Russia is
open'' to investment.
</P>
<P>
   He said the revitalized Samotlor field will produce up to
360,000 barrels a day of oil next year, of which 140,000 barrels
will be exported.
</P>
<P>
   The loan money will be provided by the New York branch of
Commerzbank AG of Germany as part of an estimated three-year
project to stop the decline, and maintain and increase the
production of the portion of the Samotlor field controlled by
Tyumen Oil.
</P>
<P>
   The $292 million is part of what will eventually be a $672
million loan package. Some $509 million of that will be guaranteed
by the Export-Import Bank, the largest ever guaranteed by the bank
to a Russian company.
</P>
<P>
   The loan package was five years in the making. The State
Department gave the go-ahead for the deal in March after putting it
on hold in December because of concerns about Tyumen's business
practices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
