<HEADLINE> Three dead in Atlantic City shooting  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - A man with an assault rifle opened
fire on a car stopped at a red light about two miles west of the
city's Boardwalk casino district Friday, killing three of the four
occupants. At least 24 shots were fired into the vehicle,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth man in the car was slightly injured by flying glass,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings occurred about 4 a.m. near a remote parking lot
for casino workers.
</P>
<P>
   The assailant remained at large Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic County Prosecutor Jeffrey Blitz said investigators are
convinced the assailant and his victims knew each other.
</P>
<P>
   A suspect was being sought, Blitz said, but he would not release
the person's identity.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were identified only as black males in their 20s
from the Atlantic City and Pleasantville area. Autopsies were being
performed Friday afternoon, Blitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Blitz said the driver of the 1989 Honda Accord exited the car
and tried to flee but was gunned down in the road. Passengers in
the front seat and left rear seat were killed by gunshots, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether the shots were fired from another
vehicle or the assailant was on foot.
</P>
<P>
   The Honda with two bodies inside was discovered in a marshy area
alongside the road - U.S. 30, known locally as the White Horse Pike
- about 100 yards from where the driver's body was found.
</P>
<P>
   Blitz would not say if the man who survived was an accomplice of
the shooter. He was taken to a local hospital for treatment, but
was not admitted. It was not clear if he remained in police
custody.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings happened near the entrance to a parking lot for
employees of marina district casinos, but Blitz said there was no
indication the incident had any connection to casinos or casino
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The crime scene is about one mile west of the Harrah's Atlantic
City and Trump Marina casinos.
</P>
<P>
   A section of the eastbound White Horse Pike between Absecon and
Atlantic City was closed for 4&AMP;frac12; hours as investigators and members
of the Atlantic County Medical Examiner's Office examined the scene
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic City-bound traffic was rerouted to the Atlantic City
Expressway, causing long delays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
