<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Marks Bombing Anniversary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Muscovites heaped carnations Friday on a memorial
cross commemorating an apartment bombing a year ago that killed 93
people and helped prompt Russia to send troops back into breakaway
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials blamed Chechen rebels for the bombing in
southeastern Moscow and three others last September -- attacks that
rattled the nation and heightened fears that the government was
powerless against crime.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family of the victims gathered Friday at the empty
lot that is all that remains of the apartment building. They
embraced, cried and laid flowers on a memorial stone and cross. A
small chapel is to be erected on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   The blast collapsed all nine stories in the center section of
the block-long building. The rest was later demolished.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing similar had ever happened in Russia or the Soviet
Union. What happened last year, we couldn't have imagined in our
worst nightmares,'' Viktor Zakharov, chief of the Federal Security
Service's Moscow branch, said in an interview published Friday in
the Kommersant newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   He said investigators have determined the chain of events
leading up to the bombings and the guilty parties. He claimed a
prominent warlord in Chechnya, a Jordanian who goes by only one
name, Khattab, had paid $500,000 to the man who allegedly organized
the two Moscow bombings, Achimez Gochiyayev.
</P>
<P>
   Police have said 33 suspects are in custody, but others,
including Khattab and Gochiyayev, are at large in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin responded by sending troops into Chechnya, where
lawlessness had become rampant after Russian troops withdrew at the
end of a 1994-96 war against separatists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
