<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Church Asks for Pardon  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- The top Roman Catholic official
in Argentina said Friday the church would ask forgiveness for its
role during the country's military dictatorship and other past
errors.
</P>
<P>
   The church plans to make the apology late Friday at the National
Eucharist Congress, the central event of its Millennial
celebration. The congress, which hopes to draw 100,000 pilgrims,
takes place in Cordoba, Argentina's second-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to confess before God everything we have done badly,''
Monsignor Estanislao Karlic, president of Argentina's Episcopal
Conference, told reporters. The Argentine church was known for its
conservative stance during the 1976-83 dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Karlic added that he hopes the apology would a starting point
''for the reconciliation of all Argentines.''
</P>
<P>
   The apology comes six months after Pope John Paul II asked for
forgiveness for the church's past errors -- including its role
during the Nazi Holocaust and other acts of political and religious
repression.
</P>
<P>
   The Argentine church had made a self-criticism for its role in
the dictatorship, in 1996 saying ''all that we did was not enough
to prevent such horror.''
</P>
<P>
   But the statement was widely considered as insufficient and
there has been mounting pressure for a fuller apology.
</P>
<P>
   The government estimates 9,000 people disappeared in the
dictatorship and are believed to have been killed. Human rights
groups put the death toll at up to 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Critics accuse the church hierarchy of giving official sanction
to the military government and doing little to prevent the human
rights abuses that took place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-08-00 1612 </TRAILER>
