<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen To Indonesia: Restore Calm  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- On President Clinton's instructions, Defense
Secretary William Cohen is to tell Indonesian leaders next week
that the army must restore security to East and West Timor or risk
losing country's international support.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen will be in Indonesia next week as part of a six-nation
Asian tour. The Pentagon said Friday that Cohen expects to meet
with President Abdurrahman Wahid and senior leaders of the
Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon official, previewing Cohen's trip on condition he not
be identified, said the secretary's message to the Indonesians will
be strong: ''Indonesia's failure to protect an American citizen and
other international aid workers, and the more general failure of
the Indonesian army to provide security for the international
relief operations, threaten to destroy the international good will
toward Indonesia at a time when it needs it most.''
</P>
<P>
   In an address Wednesday to the U.N. Millennium Summit in New
York, Clinton noted the deaths Wednesday of an American and two
other U.N. workers at the hands of a mob led by pro-Indonesian
militia gangs in West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The president urged Indonesian authorities ''to bring those
responsible to justice, to disarm and disband the militias and to
take all necessary steps to insure the safety of those continuing
to work on humanitarian goals there.''
</P>
<P>
   Wahid, in New York for the global summit, insisted Friday that
''everything is under control'' despite reports of more slayings by
militiamen.
</P>
<P>
   The militias are the same gangs that, with backing from elements
in the Indonesian military, wreaked destruction in East Timor after
island residents voted for independence in an August 1999
referendum. Militiamen were pushed into the western part of Timor
Island when U.N. peacekeepers took control in the east.
</P>
<P>
   After that episode, the Clinton administration cut off
military-to-military relations with Indonesia. The Pentagon said
Friday the administration was not yet prepared to resume military
contacts, but its ultimate goal is to bring about the kinds of
conditions in Indonesia that would permit such ties.
</P>
<P>
   On his most recent visit to Indonesia, last September, Cohen
accused the military of ''aiding and abetting'' militia violence
against civilians in East Timor, which is now administered by the
United Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
