<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irish Leader Invites Clinton  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern invited
President Clinton to return to Ireland for a last visit as
president, but the White House said Friday no trip is planned.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern told Clinton that a power-sharing government is back on
track in Northern Ireland, and that sectarian violence was kept to
a minimum during the often-volatile summer marching season.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders met while both were attending the U.N.
Millennium Summit. If Clinton does not make a trip to Ireland, it
is likely their last meeting before Clinton leaves office in
January, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ahern said to the president, 'We'd love to have you back.' The
president said, 'I'd love to go back,' but we can't plan anything
now,'' a senior administration official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Clinton
did not condition a trip on further progress toward peace in
Northern Ireland, although that has been a sticking point before.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was greeted warmly during an Irish trip in 1998, and
said last year he would go to Belfast ''at the drop of a hat if
there is some contribution I can make to the ongoing peace process
and the work still to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who often mentions his own Irish heritage as a preface
to discussions of ethnic and religious divisions, has taken a
direct interest in the long process to end sectarian violence in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   He helped broker the 1998 Good Friday peace agreement that
established a power-sharing government with representatives of
pro-British Northern Ireland unionists and Sinn Fein, the mainly
Roman Catholic party linked to the outlawed Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared dispirited earlier this year when the process
faltered, but in May, he hailed the decision of Northern Ireland's
Protestants to revive the power-sharing government.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to meet next week at the White House with David
Trimble, leader of the main Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists;
and Seamus Mallon, a leader of the moderate Roman Catholic Social
Democratic and Labor Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
