<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court says some evidence should have been released during Diallo trial </HEADLINE>
By HADLEY PAWLAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Judge Joseph Teresi was not acting within
the law when he denied the media access to documents in evidence in
the high profile Amadou Diallo murder trial, the Appellate Division
of state Supreme Court noted Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Existing law does not permit the blanket denial of access to
documentary trial exhibits,'' the Appellate Division wrote. That
was noted in a judgment that dismissed on procedural grounds the
media's petition for access to the records during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The petition by seven news organization was dismissed as moot
because the four New York City police officers on trial have since
been acquitted and the evidence is now available to the public. The
trial ended in February.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's disappointing that the appellate court recognized that a
blanket denial of public access to documentary trial exhibits is
impermissible, but nevertheless refused to vindicate the public's
right on a procedural basis,'' said Michael Grygiel, a First
Amendment lawyer who represented the news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Grygiel is considering an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo, an African immigrant, was shot and killed in the Bronx
in February 1999. Teresi, an Albany County Supreme Court judge,
took over the case when courts determined pretrial publicity in the
Bronx had made it impossible to select an unbiased jury there.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Teresi didn't allow the press access to
evidence, including police and coroner's reports that were
discussed during cross examination. He said doing so could impair
''the integrity of the evidence and interfere with the orderly
conduct of the trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Access to those documents could have helped reporters understand
the testimony, according to Grygiel. He added that denied access
may have impeded reporters' ability to cover the news.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press, Daily News, Newsday, the New York Post,
The New York Times, the Albany Times Union and the New York Law
Journal, challenged Teresi's actions in the Diallo case.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the state Attorney General's Office, which
represented Teresi, said the Appellate Division ''ruled
appropriately in the matter,'' but would not comment further.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-08-00 1629 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
