<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New NHTSA Head in Eye of Storm  </HEADLINE>
By NEDRA PICKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- WANTED: Manager to lead agency at center of
huge consumer product safety case. Must be willing to face angry
lawmakers, critical media. Expected to initiate policy changes and
persuade Republican Congress to increase budget. May be replaced in
January when new president takes office.
</P>
<P>
   This is the job Sue Bailey took over three weeks ago when she
became administrator of the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the physician and former Navy Reserve officer has
been in the middle of the maelstrom over the recall of 6.5 million
Firestone tires. The brands of tires recalled have been linked to
at least 88 U.S. traffic deaths and dozens more overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey has earned plaudits for making herself available to the
media, going before congressional panels to explain the agency's
positions and remaining generally upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't think I'd ever feel as good about working any place
as the Pentagon, but I feel that good here because we are saving
lives,'' Bailey told reporters Friday.
</P>
<P>
   NHTSA -- pronounced nit-sah -- is the federal agency under the
U.S. Department of Transportation responsible for improving
automotive safety. The agency sets and enforces safety standards
for vehicles and investigates possible defects.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's actions are almost always opposed by the auto
industry and its well-funded lobbyists on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton nominated Bailey for NHTSA's top job this
summer when she was an assistant secretary of defense and the first
woman to lead the Military Health System, responsible for the
medical care of 8.2 million military personnel. Before that she
worked in private medical administration and was in the U.S. Navy
Reserves, reaching the rank of lieutenant commander.
</P>
<P>
   Former NHTSA Administrator Joan Claybrook, now president of
consumer advocacy group Public Citizen that often criticizes the
agency, said the job is high-pressure even without something like
the Firestone recall.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think she's doing a pretty good job,'' Claybrook said of
Bailey. ''It's a very tough position to be put in the middle of a
huge controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   NHTSA has been criticized for not acting sooner to alert the
public about the Firestone tires, but most of the anger has been
directed at Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. and Ford Motor Co., which
had data indicating problems long before NHTSA was contacted.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey has fiercely defended the agency, saying it acted as soon
as it had enough evidence to start an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   When she testifies in front of a third congressional panel
investigating the case next week, Bailey said she will ask for more
funding and resources so the agency can uncover problems sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Highway Traffic Safety Administration:
http://www.nhtsa.gov
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone: http://www.bridgestone-firestone.com
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co.: http://www.ford.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-08-00 1638 </TRAILER>
