<DOCNO> APW20000908.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $adv11  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Before Hillary Rodham Clinton can truly
proclaim herself the Democratic Party's U.S. Senate candidate
against Rep. Rick Lazio, she must win a primary Tuesday against a
little-known physician from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   And, ''Grandpa Munster'' is at it again. Cigar-chomping actor Al
Lewis, who ran unsuccessfully for governor of New York in 1998 as
the Green Party's candidate, faces a three-way primary for that
party's Senate nomination this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McMahon, a 39-year-old orthopedic surgeon, managed to force
Clinton into a primary by collecting the signatures of more than
40,000 Democrats across the state. He needed just 15,000. She got
on the ballot by being the unanimous choice of the Democratic state
convention.
</P>
<P>
   While McMahon has boasted of pulling off a primary upset, the
Clinton camp and the state's Democratic Party hierarchy, which is
solidly behind the first lady, have largely ignored the doctor's
challenge. McMahon has been met by sparse crowds as he tours the
state. Many of those who do show up wonder who he is.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, greeted like a celebrity at most stops, has
declined to debate him.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're focused on the real debate in this race - the one
between Mrs. Clinton and Mr. Lazio,'' Clinton spokesman Howard
Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican until 1997, McMahon has stressed Clinton's lack of
New York roots and his familiarity with health care issues as
reasons to vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who would you rather have solving the problems of health care
- a doctor from New York or a lawyer from Arkansas?'' he asked
during a campaign stop outside the state Capitol on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   New York pollster Lee Miringoff of Marist College's Institute
for Public Opinion said Clinton should have little trouble sending
McMahon back to his medical practice and that the challenge won't
get much attention unless he approaches or breaks the 30 percent
mark. Even then, according to Miringoff, the results would mean
little given the expected low turnout for the state primary.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would reflect that there is some anti-Hillary stuff there,
which we already know,'' the independent pollster said.
</P>
<P>
   There are almost 5 million enrolled Democrats in the state who
are eligible to vote in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Polls for the primary are open from 6 a.m. to 9 p.m. in New
York, on Long Island and in Westchester, Rockland, Orange and Erie
counties. They are open from noon to 9 p.m. in the state's other 51
counties.
</P>
<P>
   In the unlikely event that Clinton loses the Democratic primary,
she will remain on the November ballot as the candidate of the
state's Liberal and union-backed Working Families parties.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has no Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   There are other U.S. Senate primaries in New York on Tuesday,
including:
</P>
<P>
   -Actor-comedian-political activist Lewis, who played ''Grandpa''
in ''The Munsters'' television series, faces a three-way Green
Party primary against Ronnie Dugger, the founding editor of the
Texas Observer who has written biographies of both Lyndon Johnson
and Ronald Reagan; and Mark Dunau, an organic farmer. Results of
the Green Party primary may not be known for several days after the
vote because paper ballots are being used in New York City for that
race.
</P>
<P>
   -Former Watertown Mayor Jeff Graham faces Jeff Beller, an Albany
area advocate for renewable energy, in the battle for the
Independence Party nomination. It is the New York arm of the
national Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   -Republican Louis Wein, who ran unsuccessfully for governor in
1990 on the Right to Life Party's line, is facing John Adefope, a
telephone company engineer, for the anti-abortion party's Senate
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   End Adv
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-08-00 1644 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000908.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Affairs head apologies for agency's 'legacy of racism'  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - The head of the federal Bureau of Indian
Affairs apologized Friday for the agency's ''legacy of racism and
inhumanity'' that included massacres, forced relocations of tribes
and attempts to wipe out Indian languages and cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ''By accepting this legacy, we accept also the moral
responsibility of putting things right,'' Kevin Gover, a Pawnee
Indian, said in an emotional speech marking the agency's 175th
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Gover said he was apologizing on behalf of the BIA, not the
federal government as a whole. Still, he is the highest-ranking
U.S. official ever to make such a statement regarding the treatment
of American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The audience of about 300 tribal leaders, BIA employees and
federal officials stood and cheered as a teary-eyed Gover finished
the speech.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought it was a very heroic and historic moment,'' said
Susan Masten, chairwoman of California's Yurok tribe and president
of the National Congress of American Indians. ''For us, there was a
lot of emotion in that apology. It's important for us to begin to
heal from what has been done since non-Indian contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Tortalita, the governor of New Mexico's Acoma Pueblo
tribe, welcomed the apology but said, ''If we could get an apology
from the whole government, that would be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gover's statement did not come from the White House,
President Clinton's chief adviser on Indian issues, Lynn Cutler,
said Gover sent her a copy of his speech late Thursday and the
White House did not object to it.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's government has formally apologized for abuses in
government-run boarding schools for Indians but has rejected calls
for a broader apology. Australian Prime Minister John Howard also
has rebuffed repeated calls for an apology to that country's
Aboriginal population for similar abuses there.
</P>
<P>
   Gover recited a litany of wrongs the BIA inflicted on Indians
since its creation as the Indian Office of the War Department.
Estimates vary widely, but the agency is believed responsible for
the deaths of hundreds of thousands of Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ''This agency participated in the ethnic cleansing that befell
the Western tribes,'' Gover said. ''It must be acknowledged that
the deliberate spread of disease, the decimation of the mighty
bison herds, the use of the poison alcohol to destroy mind and
body, and the cowardly killing of women and children made for
tragedy on a scale so ghastly that it cannot be dismissed as merely
the inevitable consequence of the clash of competing ways of
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The misery continued after the BIA became part of the Interior
Department in 1849, Gover said. Children were brutalized in BIA-run
boarding schools, Indian languages and religious practices were
banned and traditional tribal governments were eliminated, he said.
The high rates of alcoholism, suicide and violence in Indian
communities today are the result, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Poverty, ignorance and disease have been the product of this
agency's work,'' Gover said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 90 percent of the BIA's 10,000 employees are Indian and the
agency has changed into an advocate for tribal governments.
</P>
<P>
   ''Never again will we attack your religions, your languages,
your rituals, or any of your tribal ways,'' Gover promised. ''Never
again will we seize your children, nor teach them to be ashamed of
who they are. Never again.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Bureau of Indian Affairs:
http://www.doi.gov/bureau-indian-affairs.html
</P>
<P>
   National Congress of American Indians: http://www.ncai.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-08-00 1651 </TRAILER>
