<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet pedophilia charge against Catholic school leader  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - The principal of a Catholic grade
school in the Bronx was arrested Friday and accused of sending
sexually explicit images of children over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   James Irwin, 51, of Yonkers, principal of Our Lady of Mount
Carmel school, pleaded innocent at his arraignment in Yonkers City
Court. He did not return a phone call to his home.
</P>
<P>
   Westchester District Attorney Jeanine Pirro said the children in
the photographs apparently were not from Mount Carmel, which
enrolls about 290 children aged 4 to 14.
</P>
<P>
   At the school on Bathgate Avenue, only half a day of classes had
been scheduled, and the children had been sent home before parents
could be notified of Irwin's arrest. Afterward, some teachers had a
meeting at the school, but questions were referred to Monsignor
John Ruvo, the pastor, and then to Joseph Zwilling, a spokesman for
the Archdiocese of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Zwilling said Irwin, the school's principal for 15 years,
''won't be going back to Our Lady of Mount Carmel.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We've never had any complaints or indications of anything
being amiss with him,'' Zwilling said. ''We were very surprised to
learn this morning that he had been arrested. ... We will be
looking, investigating as much as we possibly can to see if there's
anything in the past, any activity that we may have missed or not
been aware of at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin was the 36th man charged in Westchester County in
connection with Internet pedophilia in the four years since the
district attorney established an office targeting the offense.
Seven other cases are pending and the other 28 have all brought
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of those men, Irwin was caught in a sting involving an
undercover agent.
</P>
<P>
   In his case, the agent posed as a man interested in child
pornography, Pirro said. After a discussion online, ''This
defendant indicated that he was willing to send to the investigator
images of children engaged in sexual activity, and that's just what
he did.'' The alleged offense occurred between Aug. 2 and Sept. 1,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin was charged with seven counts of promoting an obscene
sexual performance by a minor. He could be sentenced to seven years
in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Agents seized his home computer, a Gateway laptop, which was
displayed at Pirro's news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''This computer, in addition to the records of America Online as
well as the communications with the undercover from my office, will
substantiate the felony charges,'' the district attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the origin of the pictures, Pirro said, ''Our
investigation will continue to find out who is making these images,
who is transmitting them and who is in possession of them.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The Internet, as positive and as wonderful an innovation as it
is, is a tool for pedophiles,'' Pirro said. ''They're out there
looking for children, our children, to engage in sexual activity
with, or as in a case like this, promoting obscene sexual
performances by children. This is the reality of today's world.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, 14 Cox Ave., Yonkers.
</P>
<P>
   Our Lady of Mount Carmel School, 2465 Bathgate Ave., the Bronx.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
