<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> America feasts on double-fried frites, boutique beer -- and Belgian royalty </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Forget Diana and Charles, of the historic 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Philippe and Mathilde, of Belgium, a pair of practical
royals fit for the 21st.
</P>
<P>
   The crown prince and his suave princess are set for a five-day,
17-event royal tour of New York meant to crown double-fried frites
(known to culinary commoners as french fries) and beer as stylish -
and profitable. That even means dropping by a Manhattan supermarket
to tout all things Belgian.
</P>
<P>
   The new royals have been the centerpiece of Europe's fantasy
life since their December wedding bells, heard by tens of
thousands, with F-16s flying over the palace in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   But after they fly into New York on Saturday, accompanied by a
phalanx of European media, the prince will be ringing the opening
bell at the New York Stock Exchange. And he'll be dipping into
dollars - selling Belgian products.
</P>
<P>
   Why the sudden fascination with a country of 10 million whose
image has often paled against its southern neighbor, France?
</P>
<P>
   This is the New World, ever in search of fresh things to taste,
drink and see.
</P>
<P>
   And ''Belgium is a well-kept secret that deserves to be better
known by many more Americans,'' the prince said before the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, New York has fallen hard for things Belgian, sprouting
restaurants like Belgo, an East Village eatery that serves mussels
20 ways and 101 beers with names like Lucifer and Delirium Tremens
to a twentysomething crowd; its floor-to-ceiling design ''bands''
are patterned after the growth rings of the mussel shell.
</P>
<P>
   A lower Manhattan neighborhood in the West Village, peppered
with bistros and other Belgian eateries, is dubbed Little Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Belgian chocolates, Godiva has been joined by
such rarefied producers as Hans Burie, which offers the White House
handmade in chocolate and an all-chocolate, life-size car, or
Nirvana, ''the best chocolates this side of heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   The royal couple will blitz Manhattan, from a fund-raiser for
the Belgian-American Chamber of Commerce at the very exclusive
Metropolitan Club to a presentation to show it's not all about
hedonism - a hard-sell about Belgian biotechnology at the World
Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, Belgium's future king wields power with real
political teeth: The constitutional monarchy appoints each new
government, uniting a linguistic patchwork of Dutch and
French-speakers often at each other's ethnic throats.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old prince and his 27-year-old princess both speak
English; he studied at Oxford and Stanford universities, and has
led other trade missions.
</P>
<P>
   The recent health problems of Belgium's King Albert II, 66, have
started tongues wagging that he might yield the throne to his son.
</P>
<P>
   But, although the prince drives a Porsche and flies F-16s, he's
no fast-lane eye-catcher. As in the case of Britain's reserved
Prince Charles and the scintillating Princess Diana, it took the
''Mathilde Factor'' for the Belgian royals to seduce the world.
</P>
<P>
   After a secret three-year courtship, the prince suddenly
announced his betrothal last autumn to Mathilde d'Udekem d'Acoz, a
young aristocrat working as a speech therapist. She is to become
the first Belgian-born queen in her nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the young woman will hit the South Bronx to visit a
halfway house run by a Belgian nun who is a chaplain at Rikers
Island jail.
</P>
<P>
   And, three years after the death of Diana - as beloved in New
York as at home - America will get a look at a new princess dubbed
the ''Queen of Hearts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-08-00 1707 </TRAILER>
