<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals judge allows Labor Day Parade participate to cook  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A state appeals court judge, overruling the city
and a lower court decision, said Friday that participants in
Saturday's Labor Day Parade will be allowed limited outdoor cooking
privileges.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Richard Wallach of the State Supreme Court's Appellate
Division said cooked food and food service from vehicles will be
allowed from 10 a.m. until 3 p.m. in the parade's staging area,
from 44th to 48th streets between Fifth and Madison avenues.
</P>
<P>
   However, Wallach limited cooked food service to ''frankfurters,
hamburgers and sausages,'' to be distributed from carts and trucks
approved by the Department of Health ''as evidenced by a currently
valid decal.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're cooking with gas now,'' said Douglas Menagh, lawyer for
the New York City Central Labor Council. The council, a group of
about 500 unions that plan and run the parade, sued the city over
rules governing the event.
</P>
<P>
   The rules, most of which have been on the books for years but
mostly unenforced, include no open-flame cooking, no food service
from parked vehicles, and no alcohol. Menagh said police didn't
tell the unions until Aug. 30 that rules governing outdoor events
would be strictly enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Menagh complained Thursday to Justice Bruce Allen that the
unions would lose hundreds of thousands of dollars if they were
prevented, on such short notice, from selling food.
</P>
<P>
   Many locals have already paid for food, services and equipment
to accommodate an expected 500,000 people at this year's
festivities, with some union locals spending close to $20,000,
Menagh argued.
</P>
<P>
   But Allen ruled in favor of the city. The judge said that
despite the unions' possible financial losses, he could not stop
the city from enforcing existing laws. On Friday, Menagh appealed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We argued that after 20 years of not enforcing these rules,
police should not be allowed to enforce them now, especially since
they only gave us 10 days notice,'' said Menagh. ''That 20 years of
silence is deafening.''
</P>
<P>
   Menagh said the unions agreed to the alcohol ban because it is
consistent with their position on public drinking.
</P>
<P>
   City Corporation Counsel Michael Hess said Wallach ''in a sense,
split the difference.'' He said the judge reiterated that open
flames are banned.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our concern, and the judge recognized that, was health and
safety,'' Hess said. ''We're very pleased with the decision. We
don't have a beef with the menu.''
</P>
<P>
   The parade starts at 11 a.m. Saturday. It will begin at 44th
Street and proceed north on Fifth Avenue to 72nd Street. The
reviewing stand is at Fifth Avenue and 69th Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-08-00 1714 </TRAILER>
