<HEADLINE> Polling firm settles dispute with Microsoft over ''spam'' blacklist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - An Internet polling company has removed
Microsoft Corp. from a federal lawsuit that accused a string of
Internet service providers of blocking correspondence with many of
its 6.6 million online panelists.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Interactive Inc., the publisher of the Harris poll, said
Friday that e-mail links have been restored with nearly 1.2 million
members served by Microsoft's Hotmail e-mail service.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the Rochester-based company dropped Microsoft from a
lawsuit filed here in July that accused more than a dozen Internet
service providers of blocking e-mail to as many as 2.7 million
panelists.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute arose when Mail Abuse Prevention System, a nonprofit
California company established to fight e-mail abuse, added Harris
to a blacklist of businesses that purportedly send unsolicited,
bulk e-mails or ''spam'' - an accusation the market research
company denies.
</P>
<P>
   The company also dropped America Online Inc. from its lawsuit in
August, but is seeking unspecified damages from Redwood City,
Calif.-based MAPS as well as AltaVista Co. and six other service
providers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our e-mail is getting through to over 98 percent of our
members,'' said Harris spokesman Ben Black. ''We're in negotiations
with all the ISPs (Internet service providers) and the negotiations
are going extremely well.''
</P>
<P>
   Some ISPs dropped from the lawsuit, he said, ''didn't even
realize they were blocking us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
