<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor asks council to stop bear hunt  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman wants New Jersey's
first planned bear hunt in three decades stopped, and has asked the
state Fish and Game Council to call it off.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said Friday she would allow local police to kill bears
deemed dangerous as a way to combat the state's growing bear
nuisance problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our strategy recognizes that potentially dangerous contacts
between bears and humans in New Jersey have been on a dramatic
increase and it authorizes lethal force on those bears that pose an
immediate threat,'' Whitman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that our bear management strategy will provide a
higher degree of overall safety than the proposed random hunt,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman does not have the legal power as governor to order the
hunt canceled, said spokesman Pete McDonough. She outlined her
request to suspend the hunt in a letter to the council Friday, 10
days before it was scheduled start.
</P>
<P>
   Fish and Game Council Chairman John W. Bradway Sr. refused to
comment on Whitman's request or what action council members plan.
The group meets Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we will discuss it, it will be in executive session. It
won't be in public,'' Bradway said. Two members asked him to hold
those discussions privately, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Whitman's five-point plan, bears considered a nuisance would
be relocated, McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a nuisance bear that has been relocated and has been tagged
returns and becomes a nuisance again, that's it. This is one strike
and you're out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor proposed more money and training for police and
increases to the Department of Environmental Protection's bear task
force. Whitman also plans public education programs designed to
limit human encounters, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is everything we've been asking her to do all along. The
hunt wasn't going to solve anybody's problems,'' said Janine Motta,
a spokeswoman for New Jersey Animal Rights Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Motta, whose group had gone to court to block the hunt, praised
Whitman's proposal to train local police because they often respond
to incidents before state experts can get there.
</P>
<P>
   The state does recognize the potential dangers with bears in
populated areas, McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have logged 29 cases where bears entered homes,
25 attacks on livestock and 40 pet attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Another 34 incidents with ''aggressive'' bears have been
reported, and 1,600 complaints from residents have been filed,
McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   The hunt is scheduled to begin Sept. 18 and is open to anyone
with a hunting license. Although the season could last until
December, wildlife officials have said hunters might reach the
175-bear harvest limit in one day.
</P>
<P>
   The Fish and Game Council ordered the first bear hunt in 29
years to curb a bear population it estimates at more than 1,000.
Residents in northern New Jersey, the heart of the bear population,
have complained the animals have broken into cars and homes, killed
pets, destroyed property and scared people.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the division has overestimated the number of bears
and hasn't researched enough alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 towns have passed resolutions opposing a bear hunt.
West Milford has joined the Animal Rights Alliance and some
residents in filing an appeal to the state Fish and Game Council
order allowing the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate overwhelmingly passed a bill calling for
cancellation of the hunt, but the Assembly did not take up the
measure before it ended its session for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm certainly encouraged that the governor's office is doing
what they can to postpone the hunt,'' bill sponsor Sen. Louis C.
Bassano, R-Union, said.
</P>
<P>
   The delay gives the Assembly time to debate the hunting ban,
Bassano said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that we have the votes to pass that legislation,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, R-Salem, said in a statement he
supports Whitman's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will personally provide whatever legislative support is
necessary to fund and staff the alternative proposal offered today
by the governor,'' Collins said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-08-00 1719 </TRAILER>
