<HEADLINE> IRS Citizen Board Confirmed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two years after Congress legislated sweeping
changes in the operations of the Internal Revenue Service, the
Senate finally confirmed seven people to serve as ''private life''
members of an IRS oversight board.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate confirmed the group by voice vote Friday, ending
months of roadblocks erected by individual senators often for
unrelated reasons. The Treasury secretary and IRS commissioner are
permanent members of the nine-member board.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS overhaul gave the panel the power to review agency
operations to ensure taxpayers are treated properly and oversight
responsibilities regarding management and recommendations for
future IRS commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a talented group of people who will bring many skills
to the nation's tax agency,'' said IRS Commissioner Charles
Rossotti. ''The oversight board is an important part of our efforts
to modernize the IRS.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven approved Friday are:
</P>
<P>
   --George L. Farr, former vice chairman of American Express, to a
four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   --Charles L. Kolbe, an Iowa cattle rancher, to a three-year term.
</P>
<P>
   --Nancy Killefer, a former Treasury Department official, to a
five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   --Larry R. Levitan, former partner at Arthur Andersen &AMP; Co., to a
five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   --Steve Nickles, law professor at Wake Forest University, to a
four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   --Robert Tobias, former president of the National Treasury
Employees Union, to a five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   --Karen Hastie Williams, a partner at Crowell &AMP; Moring law firm,
to a three-year term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
