<HEADLINE> District attorney's house listed for $5.2 million  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - District Attorney Jeanine Pirro, whose
mover-and-shaker husband lost his job when he was convicted of tax
fraud, said Friday that they are selling their much-gossiped-about
home for financial reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-room house in Harrison, which was closely scrutinized for
Albert Pirro's trial, is listed for $5.2 million and has held
fabulous parties for the likes of Donald Trump and Gov. George
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   But ''it's just bricks and mortar,'' the district attorney said
during an unusual, informal chat with reporters. ''As long as the
children are with me and everybody's healthy, everything's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she had no idea where she would end up living, but
wants to remain close to her White Plains office. There has been
speculation that the district attorney, who earns $136,000 a year,
would take a higher-paying private job to make up for her husband's
lost salary as a real estate attorney and lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Pirro and his accountant, his brother Anthony, are
scheduled to be sentenced Sept. 28 for deducting $1.2 million in
personal expenses as business write-offs. Many of the expenses,
including electronic gates, a wrought-iron pigpen and a paneled
wine cellar, involved the Pirros' home.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Pirro said he spent $2 to $3 million on his defense. An
appeal could cost $1 million more.
</P>
