<HEADLINE> Naval Aviation Seen Facing Problems  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Naval aviation is suffering from serious
training and funding problems, and many aviators believe their
service's leaders are afraid to admit or address the matter
forthrightly, the Navy's inspector general said in a report
released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''From captains to airmen, we heard grave concern that Navy
leadership is either out of touch or uninformed, or just does not
care enough to address the plight of our people in meaningful
ways,'' Vice Adm. Lee F. Gunn, the inspector general, wrote of his
findings from surveying naval aviators nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The study was completed April 28 but not made public until
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Gunn said the problems in naval aviation stem from money
shortfalls and a mismatch between resources and requirements. He
also said there was evidence of ''self-inflicted wounds'' from
internal Navy decision making.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that the overall combat readiness of naval
aviation is ''largely being maintained at acceptable, albeit
declining, levels.'' To maintain this readiness, aviators and
sailors are being overworked, it said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our people have had enough, and they have not been shy about
telling us of their anger and frustration,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most serious problems in naval aviation is a decline
in training, it said. This has resulted in part from a shortage of
aircraft spare parts, which means air squadrons have fewer planes
available during the times they are training for overseas
deployments -- the most stressful period of training.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of training opportunities with advanced weapons, such as
precision-guided missiles, has taken a toll on actual Navy aviation
missions, the inspector general concluded. The rate of successful
strikes on targets in Iraq -- during missions patrolling the
''no-fly'' zone in southern Iraq -- and in Kosovo during last year's
air campaign was ''far below those that should be achievable,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of shortages of advanced weapons available for training,
some air crews drop these weapons for the first time in actual
combat.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Navy Department: http://www.navy.mil
</P>
</TEXT>
