<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NJ--Election Monitors,300  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Passaic County's elections this fall will be
overseen by a federal monitor who'll look to ensure that Hispanic
voters have full access to the balloting process.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of three federal judges Thursday appointed a former
federal prosecutor in Newark to oversee the voting.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Timpone will earn up to $275 per hour to oversee the
vote. He'll start work Monday, moving into an office at the county
administration building in Paterson.
</P>
<P>
   He'll also monitor the election for the state Attorney General's
office, which initially wanted a retired Superior Court judge to do
the work.
</P>
<P>
   ''My job, as I see it, as monitor is to see that anybody who has
the right to vote can vote,'' Timpone said. ''It's as simple as
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Timpone's appointment is the latest action by the federal
government to ensure that Passaic County's elections are accessible
to Hispanic voters. Last year, the Justice Department threatened to
sue the county and city of Passaic over an alleged pattern of
discrimination against Spanish-speaking voters.
</P>
<P>
   The county and city avoided a suit by agreeing to new procedures
in election districts with high Hispanic populations, such as
printing ballots in Spanish and English, advertising election
notices in Spanish-language newspapers, and hiring bilingual poll
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Timpone, 49, worked in the U.S. Attorney's Office in Newark from
1984 to 1995, serving as chief of special prosecutions, overseeing
corruption cases against public officials. He also was part of a
commission appointed by Gov. Whitman to investigate the failure of
the state's new auto-inspection system.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Justice Department and voting laws:
http://www.usdoj.gov/crt/voting.
</P>
</TEXT>
