<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Accusations From Banking Committee  </HEADLINE>
By MARCY GORDON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Banking Committee chairman is
accusing the Clinton administration of ''secretly'' giving some
banks approval to buy stocks of commercial companies.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, says Treasury Department officials are
trying to give banks powers they did not get under major
legislation enacted last November allowing them to expand into
other financial businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Leach made his objections public Friday in a letter to
Comptroller of the Currency John D. Hawke, Jr., whose Treasury
division oversees nationally chartered banks.
</P>
<P>
   Hawke later responded that it was appropriate for his agency to
give permission and that it did not have to be put into a formal,
written policy because it only affected three banks.
</P>
<P>
   Leach said he had learned that Hawke's office ''has given verbal
approval to at least two national banks to acquire and hold ...
shares of stock of commercial companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The banks and companies were not named.
</P>
<P>
   ''Secret verbal approvals of this extraordinary nature
communicated by (federal) bank examiners are blatant attempts ...
to change the regulatory framework'' of the financial services law
enacted last year, Leach told Hawke. In addition, he said, they
represent ''a usurpation of the Congress' law-making powers.''
</P>
<P>
   Leach's letter followed a meeting between the two men on
Wednesday at which Leach raised the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In a written response released late Friday afternoon, Hawke said
the three banks are being allowed to buy the shares and hold them
temporarily as a way to hedge their risks in derivatives
transactions. The banks use the stocks ''solely for hedging'' and
not for investment or speculative purposes, he told Leach.
</P>
<P>
   The stock purchases ''have no implications at all ... for
breaching the wall between banking and commerce,'' Hawke said.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, he maintained, since the permission only applies to
three banks, a verbal ''supervisory answer'' was sufficient rather
than a written policy.
</P>
<P>
   Derivatives, which are traded around the globe in an $80
trillion market, are complex financial instruments whose value
depends on the value or change in value of an underlying security,
commodity or asset.
</P>
<P>
   The sweeping financial services law removed Depression-era
barriers and allowed banks, securities firms and insurance
companies to get into one another's businesses. It does not,
however, allow banks to acquire commercial companies or vice versa.
Chase Manhattan Bank cannot buy General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   Some policy-makers, Leach among them, have long opposed the
mixing of banking and commerce, which they believe could expose
taxpayers to huge risk by giving commercial and industrial
companies access to federal deposit insurance and other guarantees
for banks.
</P>
<P>
   Leach asked Hawke to provide documents related to the issue by
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first time a Republican lawmaker tangled with the
presidentially appointed Comptroller. In May 1997, then-Sens.
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., and Lauch Faircloth, R-N.C., accused
Hawke's predecessor, Eugene Ludwig, of trying to expand his domain
by recruiting state-chartered banks to convert to nationally
chartered status.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   House Banking Committee: http://www.house.gov/banking
</P>
<P>
   Comptroller of the Currency: http://www.occ.treas.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
