<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Ends Down 120; Dow Falls 39  </HEADLINE>
By LISA SINGHANIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks dropped sharply Friday,
carrying the rest of the market lower, as investors reacting to a
series of earnings warnings decided to take profits from the
market's recent rally.
</P>
<P>
   The tech-dominated Nasdaq composite index closed down 119.94 at
3,978.41, giving the Nasdaq a drop of 255.92 for the week.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 39.22 at 11,220.65,
giving the average a drop of 18.13 for the week, and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 8.01 to 1,494.50, leaving it 26.27 points
lower on the week.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's declines extended a volatility streak that began
Tuesday, when traders returned from the Labor Day holiday.
Investors started the week by abandoning tech stocks in favor of
blue chips; they then turned their strategy around entirely on
Thursday and revamped it again Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst for the volatility was a series of warnings
throughout the week from companies that their upcoming earnings
reports would fall short of investors' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we're doing now is pricing in some measure of an economic
slowdown. We're looking at a fair number of warnings about
slowdowns in the third quarter,'' said Chris Dickerson, an analyst
with Global Market Strategists in Gainesville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Before the market opened Friday, an earnings warning from
Gadzoox Networks pushed its shares down $2.06 -- just over 20
percent -- to $8.25 on the Nasdaq. Gadzoox helps companies connect
computers that store large amounts of information.
</P>
<P>
   Automotive parts maker TRW's stock fell $1.44 to $43.81,
although it recovered from an earlier drop of nearly 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   First Data dropped $2.69 to $41, a more than 6 percent decline,
after a Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Corp. analyst downgraded the
credit-card transaction processor's stock to ''outperform'' from
''strong buy.''
</P>
<P>
   High-tech communications firm MPower Communications fell $3.44
to $8.88, a decline of more than 27 percent, after a Merrill Lynch
analyst cuts its rating to ''accumulate'' from ''buy.'' The
downgrade came a day after MPower revised its third- and
fourth-quarter outlook downward, saying its haste to get to the
market proved more costly than it expected.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, shares of retailer Burlington Coat Factory
surged $2.13 to $15 -- a 16 percent jump -- after it reported an
increase in its sales at stores open at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson, the Global Market Strategists analyst, said the
market's focus on tech stocks one day, then blue chips another
reflected its lack of direction.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the week, investors had bid blue chips higher. But they
shifted their attention to the Nasdaq on Thursday, sending it up
85.01, while the Dow fell 50.77 after chemical company DuPont
warned that its earnings would be down because of soft demand and
increased costs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anytime anything looks to be moving, money mangers jump into
that sector because they have to squeeze out what percentage of
profit they can. They'll jump in for a couple of days and then jump
out,'' Dickerson said. ''There's a rush almost to avoid not losing
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 7.12 at 535.70 -- down 6.21 from a
week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange. Consolidated volume came to 1.19 billion
shares, less than the 1.21 billion shares in the last session.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.23 percent.
Germany's DAX index was down 1.43 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
down 1.32 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 1.92 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
