<HEADLINE> Austria Sanctions Recommended Lifted  </HEADLINE>
By DEBORAH SEWARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- A European Union report on Friday said diplomatic
sanctions against Austria were becoming counterproductive and
should be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   In Vienna, Austrian Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel and Vice
Chancellor Susanne Riess-Passer of the far-right Freedom Party
called on the organization to end the sanctions ''exactly as fast
as'' as they were imposed in February.
</P>
<P>
   The 119-page report by a three-member panel was submitted Friday
to French President Jaques Chirac, whose country now holds the
six-month rotating European Union presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The panel was appointed by the European Union in July to examine
Austria and the sanctions that EU governments imposed to express
their discontent over the inclusion of Joerg Haider's Freedom Party
in Austria's coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The party had run an anti-immigrant campaign and Haider made
statements supportive of some aspects of the Nazi regime, though he
has denied pro-Nazi leanings.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that the Freedom Party had populist and radical
elements. It also said that the Austrian public was aware of the
existence of racism, anti-Semitism and antipathy to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the sanctions had ''already triggered
nationalistic feelings in Austria'' because they had sometimes been
interpreted as directed against the Austrian people rather than the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said the measures would be ''counterproductive''
if kept in place and therefore should be ''ended.'' It concluded
that Austria was ''respectful of common European values.''
</P>
<P>
   The document said Austria showed a level of consideration for
the rights of immigrants, refugees and minorities that was on a par
with other EU nations and in some cases was superior.
</P>
<P>
   Under the sanctions, Austria's EU partners broke off all
bilateral political contacts with the govenment in Vienna,
restricted the advancement of Austrian personnel at EU headquarters
in Brussels and snubbed Austrian ministers at routine meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatic measures also include boycotts of school trips,
cultural exchanges and military exercises.
</P>
<P>
   The three experts -- former Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari,
former Spanish Foreign Minister Marcelino Oreja and German law
expert Jochen Frowein -- turned their report over to Chirac in a
45-minute meeting. Chirac had no comment. France has been one of
Austria's most vocal critics.
</P>
<P>
   Austrian Foreign Minister Karl-Heinz Grasse, speaking in
Versailles, urged Austria's EU partners to lift the sanctions
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were imposed in one day,'' said Grasser. ''They can be
lifted swiftly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-08-00 1818 </TRAILER>
