<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's President Speaks of Taiwan  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN FACKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin said Friday
he wants to build friendly ties with the United States, and
Washington can do the same by honoring Beijing's claim to Taiwan
and granting China permanent normal trading status.
</P>
<P>
   In his only policy address while in New York for the U.N.
Millennium Summit, Jiang stressed that China was not a threat to
the United States. He said his country sought to be a constructive
member of the international community, a goal the United States
could help bring about by supporting China's efforts to modernize
its economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''A developed China will play a positive role in maintaining
world peace and stability and will by no means pose a threat to
anybody,'' Jiang told a luncheon attended by more than 300 U.S.
business executives.
</P>
<P>
   However, he also reiterated warnings against what he called
''interfering in each other's internal affairs'' -- a barb aimed at
U.S. criticism of China on human rights and other issues, most
particularly Taiwan. Jiang called Taiwan the biggest issue still
dividing his country and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Taiwan question is the most important and sensitive
question in China-U.S. relations,'' he said. ''Our relations have
experienced ups and downs over the decades, most of which can be
traced to the Taiwan question.''
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan and the trade pact were among the topics covered Friday
during a 90-minute meeting between Jiang and President Clinton,
according to American officials. The two also discussed missile
proliferation, religious freedom in Tibet and China, and
developments in North and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The United States officially supports Beijing's position that
Taiwan, which split with China during the communist takeover in
1949, is still part of China and must eventually reunite with the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington has been critical of threats in the past by
Beijing to use force if Taiwan tries to declare independence.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang sought to strike a conciliatory tone, urging the United
States to honor its pledges not to support Taiwanese independence
while proclaiming a willingness to talk directly with Taiwan's
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang also spoke at length on economic ties, calling on the U.S.
Senate to pass a bill it is now debating that would give China
status as a normal trading partner, offering it the same permanent
access to U.S. markets enjoyed by most trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will vote on the bill next week. It has faced bitter
opposition by some U.S. lawmakers and labor leaders, partly out of
fears more U.S. companies will move production to low-cost
factories in China.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Friday he believed the trade legislation
would pass, though ''we still have more work to do'' to line up
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang said the measure offers a ''win-win outcome'' for his
country and the United States, both by opening China's markets to
foreign products and by strengthening China's bid to join the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-08-00 1818 </TRAILER>
