<HEADLINE> Senator's boat sinks with none aboard  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Sen. Frank Lautenberg's Filibuster got all
wet.
</P>
<P>
   The Filibuster, a powerboat owned by the New Jersey Democrat,
hit rocks and sank after breaking loose from its mooring off
Martha's Vineyard in strong winds, his office said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   No one was aboard and Lautenberg was not at his summer house on
the Massachusetts island at the time, spokeswoman Retha Sherrod
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Fin powerboat was recovered and was brought ashore to
a lot of the Martha's Vineyard Shipyard, said Judy Searle, a worker
in the yard's office.
</P>
<P>
   The Martha's Vineyard Times reported that Tisbury harbormaster
Jay Wilbur said the 29-foot twin outboard and another craft in the
outer harbor got loose Monday night during northeast winds of about
30 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not a sheltered harbor in a northeast wind,'' Wilbur told
the weekly.
</P>
<P>
   A message left Friday for Wilbur was not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg spokeswoman Retha Sherrod said the senator was
unavailable to comment Friday, but said the boat was a 25-footer.
</P>
</TEXT>
