<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jet's wreckage is spotted, surviving pilot identified  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRIGANTINE, N.J. (AP) - The wreckage of an F-16 that crashed
into the Atlantic Ocean last week was found Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Salvage crews that had been searching for a week spotted it on
the ocean floor, about two miles east of Brigantine beach,
according to Col. John Dwyer, spokesman for the New Jersey Air
National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   They will attempt to recover it Saturday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The $18 million jet, operated by the 177th Fighter Wing in Egg
Harbor Township, was ditched into the sea Aug. 31 after its engine
failed during a training exercise over the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot tried to return to the base but was worried the jet
didn't have enough power to land, so he turned around and steered
it out to sea to avoid harming people or property.
</P>
<P>
   He ejected safely and was rescued unhurt from a life raft.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot was identified Friday as Maj. David G. Haar, 41, of
Great Meadows.
</P>
<P>
   A 19-year veteran of the Air National Guard, Haar had logged
more than 2,200 hours in the air, including 1,270 in F-16s, before
the incident. He has been grounded since, pending an Air Force
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The probe will probably take about a month, Dwyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Haar's name was withheld from public release for more than a
week because Air Force investigators wanted to get the first
interview with him, before the media, Dwyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Haar could not be reached for comment Friday. The Guard said it
would not make him available for interviews, and he did not return
two telephone messages left at his home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
