<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mystery Complicates Senator's Bid  </HEADLINE>
By BRIAN BAKST
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Already regarded as vulnerable in his run
for re-election, Sen. Rod Grams is now dogged by a criminal
investigation that may tie his campaign to an e-mail attack aimed
at a Democratic challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Grams and his campaign have denied involvement. But court
documents made public Thursday show an apparent link between
Christine Gunhus, his former chief of staff and now a top campaign
aide, and e-mails intended to sour Democrats on trial lawyer Mike
Ciresi, who is locked in a primary battle.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts suggested that the mere allegation of a dirty
trick could haunt Grams. Polls already suggest the general election
will be tight no matter who Democrats nominate in Tuesday's
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ''Virtually anything that disadvantages Senator Grams, even in a
small way, may actually determine the outcome,'' said Steve Smith,
a congressional scholar at the University of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators searched Gunhus' house after finding that an
e-mail account used to send the messages was accessed at least four
times from a phone line registered to her. The e-mails may have
broken laws that require campaign literature to be labeled with its
source.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly sent by a concerned Democrat, the e-mails portrayed
Ciresi as a hypocrite whose law firm defended many corporate
wrongdoers at the same time he was playing up an image as a legal
fighter for important causes. Ciresi was the lead attorney in
Minnesota's lawsuit against tobacco companies, which ended in a
$6.1 billion settlement for the state.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the first e-mails were sent, in May, Ciresi was
considered a front-runner in the race and was hoping to get the
party endorsement. Instead, the endorsement went to state Sen.
Jerry Janezich, a more lightly regarded candidate without Ciresi's
considerable financial resources.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Janecek, a Republican strategist, said the longer the case
looms, the bigger liability it becomes. Grams and Gunhus have been
forceful in their denials, but Janecek said they should be airing
their defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stuff like this does not happen in a court of law; it happens
in the court of public opinion,'' she said. ''Even though you're
theoretically in a judicial proceeding, in politics you have to
play it differently.''
</P>
<P>
   The race for Grams' seat is one of about a dozen Senate races
being closely watched around the nation. The nonpartisan Rothenberg
Political Report, a Washington-based newsletter, rates Grams as
''highly vulnerable,'' its worst category for a senator facing
re-election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
