<HEADLINE> Corzine schedules three debates, two on network TV; Franks agrees  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - U.S. Senate candidate Jon Corzine announced
Friday he has scheduled three debates with Republican opponent Bob
Franks, two of them on network television.
</P>
<P>
   Franks immediately accepted the dates, but kept up his criticism
of the free-spending Democrat for his refusal to appear with Franks
side by side more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   One-hour debates with tentative October dates would be telecast
on two Sundays on ABC and CBS network television affiliates in New
York and Philadelphia. A third debate is to be scheduled on New
Jersey Network (NJN) public television.
</P>
<P>
   Franks has been attacking Corzine for refusing a more aggressive
schedule of 21 debates - one in each county in the state - that the
Republican has been pushing for since June.
</P>
<P>
   The Corzine campaign said this schedule of debates should end
any quarreling about the issue. Campaign spokesman Tom Shea has
said no statewide candidates in New Jersey have ever agreed to more
than three debates in recent elections.
</P>
<P>
   During the primary campaign against former Gov. Jim Florio,
Corzine would not agree to any network television debates while
spending some $12 million on those same TV stations for ads over
the course of eight weeks. He debated Florio four times, including
at a cable TV network studio and on NJN.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said he hoped the three October debates will settle the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am happy that the debate about the debates is behind us,''
Corzine said, chastising the Franks campaign for refusing to help
arrange these debates jointly. ''It is unfortunate that we had to
do it alone, but I am glad that we got it done. New Jersey voters
deserve no less.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks said he believes the candidates should appear more
frequently. ''The people of New Jersey are entitled to see Jon
Corzine and Bob Franks on the same platform answering the same
questions in a variety of forums,'' and at alternate sites in the
state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At their last joint appearance at a VFW forum on Aug. 29, Franks
complained that Corzine required that Franks remain outside the
auditorium while Corzine gave a speech and answered questions from
a panel.
</P>
<P>
   The Corzine campaign, in turn, complained one of the three panel
members asking the questions was a prominent Republican figure in
state government. The Democrat told the audience that night he
preferred forums because they gave candidates and audiences a
chance for direct discussion without interruptions from a political
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   They are scheduled to appear together again Saturday at a state
Conference of Mayors meeting in Cumberland County.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative dates for broadcast of the CBS debate are Oct. 1
or Oct. 8, to be broadcast on the New York's WCBS-TV Channel 2 and
Philadelphia's KYW-TV Channel 3. It will be cosponsored by the
Star-Ledger of Newark.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC debate is set for broadcast Oct. 22 on WABC-TV New York
Channel 7 and WPVI-TV Philadelphia Channel 6. It will be
cosponsored by the Philadelphia Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   The third debate to be aired on NJN has not yet been given a
date. It is to be cosponsored by The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the primary season, the final debate of the series
is early, a full 16 days before Election Day.
--:
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.votecorzine.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.bobfranks.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
