<HEADLINE> Cheney unfazed by Republican ad praising Lieberman  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELTON, Conn. (AP) - While Republican vice presidential
candidate Dick Cheney campaigned in Connecticut Friday, a member of
his own party was running TV ads in the state lauding the integrity
of Cheney's opponent, U.S. Sen. Joseph Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   During the stop in Lieberman's home state, Cheney said he did
not feel slighted by the television ad by Mark Nielsen, a
Republican who is challenging Democratic U.S. Rep. James Maloney
for the 5th District seat in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In the ad, images of Lieberman, former President George Bush and
U.S. Sen. John McCain are shown as a narrator says, ''Today, when
America wants leaders with honesty and integrity...''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said he was not embarrassed by the ad, even though it
praises his opponent, Lieberman, and does not show either him or
his running mate, Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''My attitude, when I get out around the country, is (to)
encourage Republican candidates to do whatever they can to get
elected, and if Mr. Nielsen thinks that'll help him get elected in
Connecticut, more power to him,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney spoke with reporters before meeting with senior citizens
in Shelton to talk about Medicare and prescription drugs. He also
was scheduled to attend a Greenwich fund-raiser that was expected
to raise $250,000 for the state Republican party.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen, who is challenging Maloney for the second time after a
close race in 1998, said his TV ad was intended to contrast
Lieberman's reputation for integrity with the reputation of
Maloney.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen said the ad was not meant to slight Cheney. He said he
used Lieberman because he is so well-known in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is a useful example that I can use in pointing out my
opponent's deficiencies,'' Nielsen said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The ads began running Friday on the NBC, CBS, ABC and Fox
affiliates in the Hartford-New Haven market.
</P>
<P>
   In the ad, Nielsen says Maloney took tens of thousands of
dollars in illegal campaign money, then ''let his brother take the
fall and serve the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Maloney was not charged with violating any election laws. His
brother, Robert, was convicted in 1997 for violating federal
election law by reimbursing some donors for contributions he
solicited.
</P>
<P>
   The ad also claims Maloney broke his promise not to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney on Friday blasted Nielsen, saying the ad contains ''one
falsehood after another.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a gross embarrassment to the Nielsen campaign,''
Maloney said.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney noted that the U.S. attorney's office determined there
was no evidence that he had any knowledge of his brother's
activities and that when he learned about the violation, he
refunded the money.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney said he consistently has voted for tax cuts and was not
the big spender described by Nielsen in the ad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
