<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Continental plane aborts takeoff after engine fails  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - The National Transportation Safety Board is
investigating why an engine on a Continental Airlines DC-10 spewed
parts onto the runway at Newark International Airport, causing the
pilot to abort a takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   No one was injured in Tuesday's incident, the second time in
less than five months that a Continental DC-10 engine suffered an
''uncontained engine failure'' at Newark airport, one of its hubs.
</P>
<P>
   In such failures, which are uncommon, parts go through the
engine covering. The engines are designed to eject parts out the
rear, which poses less of a threat to the aircraft and its
occupants, an aviation expert said.
</P>
<P>
   The Newark incidents involved different aircraft, but both were
Flight 60, from Newark to Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are isolated, separate instances of engine failure,''
Continental spokesman David Messing said from the airline's Houston
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   All engines on Continental's 24 DC-10s are made by General
Electric Co., Messing said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We use them, the manufacturer, exclusively for all
overhauls,'' he said. Messing could not say when the most recent
maintenance was performed on the engines that failed.
</P>
<P>
   GE Aircraft Engines, based in Cincinnati, performs overhauls
every few years, but routine maintenance is done by the airline, GE
spokesman Rick Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   He could not immediately provide the date of the last overhaul
for either of the engines involved, which he said were about 20 to
25 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The engine model, CF6-50, has a good service record and is the
best-selling engine for large aircraft, Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   The early indications are that both engines suffered a failure
toward the rear of the engine, not the heart, he said. As a result,
neither lost all power.
</P>
<P>
   The DC-10 is used by more than 60 airlines and has an excellent
service record, Messing said. Continental, which has more than 500
aircraft, is replacing its DC-10s with Boeing 767s over the next
two years.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB has not determined the cause of the April 25 incident.
</P>
<P>
   That plane returned to Newark 34 minutes after takeoff with two
of its three engines failing, blown tires and ruptured hydraulic
lines, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's incident took place about 7:20 p.m. when the center,
or No. 2, engine failed during takeoff, Federal Aviation
Administration spokesman Jim Peters said.
</P>
<P>
   The takeoff was aborted after sparks and debris were seen coming
from the engine. Airport workers found turbine blades and metal
debris on the runway afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The 237 passengers safely exited the plane on the runway after
the incident.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz said the engine will taken apart
by agency personnel, along with FAA and GE representatives. He
could not say when that would happen or when a cause would be
determined.
</P>
<P>
   FAA records show 25 uncontained engine failures from 1985-99,
resulting in two deaths and 16 injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're a little unusual,'' said William D. Waldock, a
professor of aeronautical science at Embry-Riddle Aeronautical
University in Prescott, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   The most common causes are metal failure or when birds are
sucked into the engine. An unbalanced turbine blade can also cause
such a failure, but that is usually detected during routine
maintenance, Waldock said.
</P>
<P>
   The GE engines are reliable, but require more attention as they
log more miles, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The real key is the maintenance. If it's maintained properly,
you can keep running them almost indefinitely,'' Waldock said.
</P>
<P>
   The Newark incidents are the latest problem for Continental
involving a DC-10. French investigators announced Monday that a
stray length of metal that gashed a tire of a supersonic Concorde,
leading to a fuel tank fire and dooming the flight, probably came
from a Continental Airlines plane that took off on the same runway
four minutes earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Continental officials are cooperating with that investigation,
but have not said that the metal part was from one of their DC-10s.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Continental Airlines: http://www.continental.com
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration: http://www.faa.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
