<HEADLINE> Impeachment PAC Cancels Starr Salute  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The political action committee raising money
for the House impeachment managers has canceled next month's salute
to former special prosecutor Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   A notice on the House Managers PAC Web site Friday said: ''We
wish to honor Judge Starr for his integrity but at this time we
feel it more appropriate to place our tribute on hold for a
possible rescheduling.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising salute was designed to help fill the coffers of
the PAC, which was formed to financially aid the 13 House
Republicans who prosecuted President Clinton in his Senate trial.
Through June 30, the PAC had raised just $76,787 and had only
$37,230 in the bank. Tickets for the salute began at $100.
</P>
<P>
   No reason for the cancellation was given, and calls to PAC
officials were not returned Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The salute was scheduled for Oct. 4, however, and that turned
out to be the week that Congress hoped to adjourn so lawmakers
could go home and campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 13 House managers, Rep. Jim Rogan, R-Calif., is at
the top of the Democratic congressional hit list this fall. He is
being challenged by state Sen. Adam Schiff in what promises to
become the most expensive House race in history. Rogan polled just
51 percent of the vote in winning re-election two years ago in a
district that went for Clinton in both 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, a solicitor general under former President Bush, was
appointed to take over the Clinton investigation by a three-judge
panel in August 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1998, he presented a voluminous and sexually
explicit report to Congress about Clinton's relationship with
former intern Monica Lewinsky, arguing that he had found
''substantial and credible information ... that may constitute
grounds for impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, the House impeached Clinton on two articles of
perjury and obstruction of justice. The Senate voted to acquit in
February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The following October, Starr resigned his post, stating in a
letter that his departure was prompted by the ''intense
politicization'' of his work.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: House Managers PAC: www.housemanagers2000.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
