<HEADLINE> Schumer opposes talk of casinos in Manhattan  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER ZACHARIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Donald Trump may have to find another way to
make his next millions, if Sen. Charles Schumer gets his way.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said Friday that Trump will ''face serious opposition''
if he tries to go forward with his reported plan to team up with an
American Indian tribe to open the world's largest casino on the
west side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Trump said in Tuesday's New York Post that if state and federal
officials approve a proposal for the St. Regis Mohawk Indians to
open a casino in the Catskills, he may propose building one with
another Indian tribe on 100 acres of underdeveloped land he owns
near the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   The billionaire developer fears that a casino in the Catskills
would siphon business away from Atlantic City, N.J., where he owns
three hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer supported the Catskills plan, which would land the new
casino 75 miles from midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   New York state law prohibits casinos, but federal law allows
them on Indian reservations. Indian tribes also can have
off-reservation land put into trust for a casino. There was no word
on which tribe Trump would be dealing with.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said the same set of criteria that led him to eagerly
support the Catskills casino proposal now leads him to adamantly
oppose building one in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ''While a casino might be a good bet for a struggling area in
need of an economic shot in the arm, it is a poor gamble for a
bustling metropolis,'' Schumer told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''A city that already boasts the Empire State Building, the
Statue of Liberty and the World Trade Center does not need the Taj
Mahal.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing surveys and meetings with community leaders, Schumer also
said Manhattan residents are strongly opposed to a local casino.
</P>
<P>
   Trump's spokeswoman said he was unavailable to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said he would support casino gambling in
New York City as long as the casinos were kept free of organized
crime and a portion of the revenue stayed in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've always felt that if they allow casino gambling in New
York, then New York City should be a part of that, because it would
be just another way of diverting money out of the city,'' Giuliani
said.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer insisted that he will do everything he can ''to make
sure it doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   New York state now has two casinos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
