<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three men shot to death in pre-dawn roadside ambush  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - A man with an assault rifle opened
fire on a car at a traffic light Friday, spraying it with bullets
and killing three of the four people inside.
</P>
<P>
   At least 24 shots were fired in the pre-dawn ambush on U.S. 30,
about two miles west of the city's Boardwalk casinos, according to
Atlantic County Prosecutor Jeffrey Blitz.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were identified as Lamont Wilson, 21, Richard White,
26, and Michael Demps, 20, all of Pleasantville. The fourth man
wasn't identified by authorities.
</P>
<P>
   They probably knew the killer, Blitz said. There was no
indication the attack was random, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, who remained at large late Friday, approached the
blue-green 1989 Honda Accord as it was stopped for a red light and
began firing, Blitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning on the driver's side, he walked around the car,
shooting at the unarmed occupants, Blitz said.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, Wilson managed to get out and flee, causing the
car - which was still in gear - to roll forward. But he was shot to
death as he ran down the highway.
</P>
<P>
   The killer then walked around the back of the car and up to the
front-seat passenger's side, firing through the windows and killing
the two passengers on the right side of the car.
</P>
<P>
   Passing motorists witnessed the 4 a.m. attack, which blew out
the back window and both windows on the right side of the car and
left seven bullet holes on the passenger's side of the front
windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's body landed about 100 yards from the spot where the car
came to rest, in a salt marsh alongside the road, next to a parking
lot for employees of Harrah's Atlantic City and Trump Marina
casinos.
</P>
<P>
   The survivor, who was sitting in the left rear seat, was injured
by flying glass but was not shot, Blitz said. He was cooperating
with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Blitz would not comment when asked whether the survivor was
purposely spared by the killer.
</P>
<P>
   He also declined comment on whether the gunman was waiting for
the victims' car at the intersection or got out of another car
stopped for the traffic light.
</P>
<P>
   Blitz would not give a motive, a physical description or any
information about what precipitated the slayings, saying he didn't
want to tip his hand. He ruled out road rage, however.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a particular interest that the suspect or suspects not
read about it until I'm prepared to make an arrest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No weapon was recovered. The spent shell casings were .223
caliber, he said. No weapon was found in the car, either.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsies were being performed on all three victims Friday. The
results were not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   A section of the eastbound highway, between Absecon and Atlantic
City, was closed for 4&AMP;frac12; hours as investigators and members of the
Atlantic County Medical Examiner's Office examined it.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic City-bound traffic was rerouted to the Atlantic City
Expressway, causing long delays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
