<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Can't Persuade Arafat  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- After a brief encounter with Yasser
Arafat, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak summed up peace efforts
with the Palestinians in two words Friday: ''No good.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak told The Associated Press he made a last-ditch approach to
the Palestinian leader before Arafat's scheduled departure for Gaza
and urged him to reach an accord in the little time remaining
before next week's self-imposed deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat was not responsive, Barak said with evident
disappointment. The prime minister said he had no meetings
scheduled with either President Clinton or Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright in New York over the weekend. But his spokesman,
Gadi Baltiansky, said the prime minister was seeing American
mediator Dennis Ross later Friday. Ross met separately with
Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations are hung up mostly over Jerusalem. Arafat is
unyielding in his demand for sovereignty over the eastern part of
the city and has resisted compromises offered by Clinton and
pleadings by Barak that the Palestinian was missing an opportunity
to gain statehood.
</P>
<P>
   In Gaza City, the Palestine Liberation Organization's Central
Council is to meet Saturday to consider whether to move forward
with a unilateral declaration of statehood Wednesday as Arafat has
indicated he would do absent an overall settlement. Albright and
other U.S. officials have cautioned Arafat they would not support
such a state.
</P>
<P>
   Next Wednesday is the deadline that Barak and Arafat set last
year for overall agreement. White House spokesman Joe Lockhart now
calls that deadline ''artificial'' and says Clinton is prepared to
keep working past it for an accord.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat met separately with Clinton on Wednesday at the
Millennium Summit that brought the two leaders and more than 100
others to New York for traffic-snarling deliberation at the United
Nations on ''soft'' international issues.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing Friday for a meeting with Irish Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern, Clinton was overheard saying: ''This Middle East thing, it's
maddening.'' The president held his arms wide apart, as if to
signify the issues are too wide to grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Second-tier Israeli and Palestinian negotiators are to resume
talks in the Middle East next week. However, pessimism prevailed.
U.S. officials said only a few weeks remain to secure a treaty, and
lower-level negotiators have scored few achievements in the past.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Clinton's mediation effort during this week's
U.N. Millennium Summit was the fate of a 36-acre walled compound in
Jerusalem's Old City. It is revered by Jews as the Temple Mount,
site of their two former Temples, and by Muslims as Haram
as-Sharif, or Noble Sanctuary, with two mosques marking the spot
where they believe Prophet Mohammed ascended to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has proposed complex sovereignty arrangements
to accommodate rival Israeli and Palestinian claims, including
placing some areas under divine sovereignty to enable both sides to
save face in accepting the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Nabil Shaath dismissed ''the idea of
God's sovereignty.'' Shaath said he believed that Arafat had
convinced Clinton ''that it is impossible to solve the issue of
Jerusalem without total Palestinian sovereignty over the city and
the holy places inside it.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak said he appealed in his Friday meeting with Arafat for
them to ''get something done'' before time runs out. But, shaking
his head, Barak said he did not get a positive reply.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said he would contemplate hard-to-accept American
proposals, provided Arafat would reciprocate.
</P>
<P>
   Many Israelis feel the prime minister has gone too far already
in virtually assuring Palestinian control of almost all the West
Bank, Gaza and some neighborhoods in Jerusalem and near suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   He may face efforts to force him from office when the Knesset,
Israel's parliament, reconvenes next month.
</P>
<P>
   Barak also has said no Israeli prime minister would ever accept
Palestinian sovereignty over the Temple Mount -- ''a cornerstone of
our identity'' -- but suggested he would not necessarily insist on
full Israeli control.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, in turn, said anything less than full Palestinian
sovereignty over all of traditionally Arab east Jerusalem,
including the Old City and its Muslim and Christian holy sites, is
out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't betray my people. I can't betray the Arabs. I can't
betray the Christians. I can't betray the Muslims,'' Arafat told
CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiator Shaath said he feels it has been a mistake to focus
on the hardest dispute, over the holy sites. Negotiators will now
try to make progress on the other issues, such as land, refugees
and borders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said both sides promised to work hard. ''But the truth
is, just look at the calendar,'' she said. ''There is not a lot of
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
