<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Torch triggers fire in Jamestown manufacturer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JAMESTOWN, N.Y. (AP) - A spark from a torch was blamed for a
fire that heavily damaged a 100-year-old building that used to
house a furniture maker.
</P>
<P>
   The fire broke out at 8:20 a.m. as workers used acetylene
torches to cut bolts off an old air ventilation system on the top
floor of the 200,000-square-foot, four-story Art Metal building. It
recently was sold and the owner planned to convert it into a
multi-use site.
</P>
<P>
   Crew members said they placed metal sheets over the rubber and
foam roof before they started cutting with the torch to reduce the
risk of a spark igniting a fire.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the damage was contained in the center of the
building and at one end, all on the fourth floor. The heavy
concrete construction - floors about six inches thick - helped
prevent major damage, a fire official said.
</P>
<P>
   Art Metal was a metal office furniture maker that employed more
than 1,400 people at its peak. The company closed in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   One firefighter suffered a deep bruise to his neck when a helmet
fell from the third floor and hit him.
</P>
<P>
   Jamestown is 58 miles southwest of Buffalo.
</P>
</TEXT>
