<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, Sept. 8, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.N. Summit Ends With Resolution
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Ending a historic three-day summit, the world's
leaders pledged today to resolve humankind's problems, with a New Millennium's
resolution promising to send every child to school and deliver millions from
destitution by 2015. Negotiated for weeks, the eight-page Millennium
Declaration, is a catalog of the world's troubles -- poverty, war, AIDS,
pollution, human rights violations and much more -- and a promise to deal with
them. ''We recognize that, in addition to our separate responsibilities to our
individual societies, we have a collective responsibility to uphold the
principles of human dignity, equality and equity at the global level,'' the
declaration reads.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush To Negotiate on Debates
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WACO, Texas (AP) -- The Bush and Gore campaigns will meet with the
presidential debate commission next week to negotiate terms for a fall series of
televised confrontations, the campaigns said today. Republican George W. Bush
had been insisting on a schedule that would include only one
commission-sponsored presidential debate and two other less-formal TV
appearances. But some supporters had raised concerns that his stance was being
read by some voters as a reluctance to debate. Al Gore, the Democratic vice
president, has said he would consider other formats only after Bush agreed to
the widely telecast commission debates.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Philippine Rebels Won't Free Hostages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- Muslim rebels backed out on a promise to free
on Friday all six European hostages they have held for months in the Philippine
jungle, making a partial offer that forced the government to cancel the entire
release, an official said. Abu Sayyaf rebel leader Ghalib ''Robot'' Andang
informed a mediator that he would only free three of the Europeans, negotiators
said. Chief government negotiator Robert Aventajado then attempted to call
Andang by satellite phone to push for the release of all six, but was unable to
reach him.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ford Extends Truck Plant Shutdown
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor has extended the shutdown of three truck factories
by one week to divert 30,000 tires toward a massive recall. The tires are needed
to fill replacement orders for 6.5 million Firestone truck tires recalled in
early August. A longer shutdown is possible, Ford said today. The plants in St.
Paul, Minn., Edison, N.J. and Hazelwood, Mo., have been closed for two weeks so
that 15-inch tires used as standard equipment on Ford Explorer/Mercury
Mountaineer sport utility vehicles and Ford Ranger pickups can be sent to Ford
and Lincoln/Mercury dealers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Jabs Bush Over Social Security
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Al Gore celebrated an ''even-up'' presidential race today
and used one of Republican rival George W. Bush's favorite lines to heckle him
about unanswered questions in his Social Security plan. Gore, at Delgado
Community College to promote his education agenda, faulted Bush for not
specifying how he would replace the Social Security money used to pay
current-day benefits, money he proposes to divert into private investment
accounts. Gore, the Democratic nominee, then appropriated a common theme in
Bush's stump speech about trusting the American people over big government.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Sees Passage of China Trade Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Concluding a whirlwind week of diplomacy, President Clinton
assured Chinese President Jiang Zemin the Senate will approve an agreement
giving Beijing permanent normal trade relations in return for slashing tariffs
on American goods sold in the vast Chinese market. The Senate is to vote next
week on the deal, the biggest trade bill of the year and one of Clinton's top
foreign policy priorities. The bill was approved by the House last May.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nasdaq Ends Down 120; Dow Falls 39
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks plummeted today, carrying the rest of the
stock market lower, as investors reacting to a series of earnings warnings
decided to take profits from the market's recent rally. The Nasdaq closed down
119.90 at 3,978.45. The Dow Jones was down 39.22 at 11,220.65 and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 8.01 to 1,494.50.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Indiana Investigating Knight Again
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- Indiana University basketball coach Bob Knight
today called ''absolutely, totally untrue'' an accusation by a 19-year-old
student that the beleaguered coach grabbed and cursed at him. The school said it
was investigating and considers the matter as ''extraordinarily serious,''
university spokesman Christopher Simpson said.
</P>
