<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cheney Promotes Prescription Drugs  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELTON, Conn. (AP) -- Campaigning on Joe Lieberman's turf
Friday, Dick Cheney promoted the GOP ticket's plan to help seniors
pay for prescription drugs and criticized a Democratic ad against
the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Another display of the Clinton-Gore routine -- attack,
exaggerate and misrepresent,'' said Cheney, the Republican vice
presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney told seniors at an assisted living center in Shelton,
Conn., that Bush's $198 billion Medicare reform and prescription
drug program was superior to Democrat Al Gore's $253 billion
prescription drug plan.
</P>
<P>
   The former defense secretary spent most of the day on the
defensive, however, with Democrats lobbing rocks at him for missing
out on a chance to vote for GOP presidential nominee George W. Bush
in the Texas primary.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Morning News reported Cheney did not vote in 14 out
of the last 16 elections. Cheney has lived primarily in Dallas for
the last several years, but registered to vote in Wyoming in July
to smooth the way for his vice presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said extensive traveling kept him from becoming involved
in state or local politics, though he said he voted in ''every
federal primary and general election in the last twenty-some
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Al Gore's campaign was quick to seize on the story.
</P>
<P>
   ''It appears that Dick Cheney did not receive a major-league
vetting by George W. Bush,'' said Chris Lehane, spokesman for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Cheney shrugged off a new poll showing his unfavorable
ratings among voters was growing. The poll, by ABC-Washington Post,
showed 42 percent of voters viewed Cheney favorably, while 20
percent viewed him negatively -- almost double his negative ratings
shown in a poll take after Bush chose him as a running mate about
six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't spend a lot of time worrying about my favorables or
unfavorables,'' Cheney told reporters. ''It's not a personality
contest in terms of the vice-presidential campaigns. It's about
which ticket can win the election.''
</P>
<P>
   The favorability ratings of Gore's running mate, Lieberman, have
nearly doubled to 46 percent from 24 percent a month ago, the poll
showed.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen percent of voters had a negative opinion of Lieberman in
the latest poll, up from 10 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman got a boost from an unlikely source -- a GOP
congressional candidate who helped arrange Cheney's visit to
Shelton. Lieberman was featured in TV ads for Mark Nielsen that
showed the Connecticut senator's picture as an example of a leader
''with honesty and integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen said he put Lieberman, whom he respects, in the ad that
began airing Friday as a contrast to his opponent, incumbent Rep.
Jim Maloney, and acknowledged that endorsing Cheney's opponent on
the day of his campaign appearance was ''unfortunate'' timing.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney shrugged that one off too. ''If Mr. Nielsen thinks
that'll help him get elected in Connecticut, more power to him. We
need his vote in Washington,'' he told local reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He ended the day at a state-party fund-raiser in Greenwich,
Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
