<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bomb Destroys Car in S. Africa  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- A car bomb exploded outside a
crowded cafe on Friday night, the latest attack in a growing
campaign of urban terror being waged in this coastal city. There
were no immediate reports of injuries, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb detonated outside the Obz Cafe, located in an area of
restaurants and bars frequented by students at the University of
Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the explosive appeared to be similar to those used
in three attacks in August.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb went off a day after a judge Pieter Theron, 50, was
assassinated. He was getting out of his car in the driveway of his
Cape Town house on Thursday when a man and woman drove past in a
stolen vehicle and killed him with five shots.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, the city -- a picturesque tourist
destination known for its tabletop mountain, pristine beaches and
vineyards -- has experienced a series of attacks against
restaurants, police stations and gay bars, which have left three
people dead and more than 100 injured. Some homes have also been
bombed.
</P>
<P>
   No one has claimed responsibility for any of them. But police
and politicians have blamed a Muslim vigilante group called People
Against Gangsterism and Drugs. About 100 members are currently
awaiting trial on a range of other charges including possessing
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   The group has repeatedly denied responsibility for the attacks
and says it does not condone violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-08-00 2041 </TRAILER>
