<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Salmonella Cases Linked to Juice  </HEADLINE>
By JANET McCONNAUGHEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Washing oranges to get germs off their peels
may not be enough to make sure the juice stays safe, the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Two salmonella outbreaks in the past 16 months have been linked
to unpasteurized juice made from sanitized oranges, CDC researchers
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The safest orange juice to drink is labeled as pasteurized or
made from concentrate, said researcher Josefa Rangel, who
investigated an April outbreak which sickened 88 people in eight
states.
</P>
<P>
   In June and July 1999, an outbreak affected 423 people in 20
states and three Canadian provinces, the CDC said. Forty-four
people were hospitalized, and one died in what was the largest
outbreak to date from orange juice contaminated during production.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies had washed or chemically treated whole oranges,
killing virtually all bacteria on their peels, before extracting
the juice, Rangel said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA is working on rules for the process and expects to have
them finished this year, agency scientist Shellee Anderson said.
She would not say whether a safety warning is being considered.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Gunter, general counsel for the National Juice Products
Association, said that, as far as she knew, the group's 68 members
either pasteurize juices or make them from concentrates, which are
heated enough to kill bacteria while the concentrates are being
made. Most major juice makers are members of that association.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Infectious Diseases Society of America:
http://www.idsociety.org/
</P>
<P>
   Centers for Disease Control: http://www.cdc.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Transcript of two days of FDA meetings about fresh juice safety:
http://vm.cfsan.fda.gov/~comm/tr991208.html
</P>
</TEXT>
