<DOCNO> APW20000908.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young Twins Set to Join NHL  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- While 19-year-old twins Daniel and
Henrik Sedin are looking forward to NHL life in Vancouver, Canucks
coach Marc Crawford is preaching patience.
</P>
<P>
   The Sedins, selected second and third overall by Vancouver in
the 1999 entry draft, are here with 22 other Canucks as the team
prepares for the upcoming NHL season with a 10-day training camp
and exhibition games against teams from the Swedish Elite League.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know they will always be of interest because of the newness
of them and because of the fact they are identical twins and are
both such high draft picks and they performed so well in other
places,'' Crawford said, comparing the attention to that received
by a young Eric Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's nothing we can do about that. But we are also very,
very conscious that they are a young part of this team and with all
young players there is a time for adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching the twins skate live for the first time, Crawford
spoke of two adjustments the Sedins must make: in hockey and
culture.
</P>
<P>
   The hockey adjustments involve a new forechecking system and
improved skating.
</P>
<P>
   ''In North America there is much more pressure on the puck
carrier right away and forechecking is much more aggressive,''
Crawford said. ''First they have to learn to become decent
forecheckers and get good anticipation and quickness with pursuit
of the puck. The other adjustment is that, when you have the puck,
the other team is going to be on you a little quicker. Over here
the puck carrier is allowed to carry the puck a little more
freely.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford quickly enrolled nine-year NHL veteran Trent Klatt as
an on-ice tutor. By pairing the Sedins with Klatt, a good
forechecker who works hard on both his skating and puck pursuit,
Crawford hopes to start the process early.
</P>
<P>
   The twins were expecting the change after meeting with Vancouver
coaches earlier this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Sweden we are standing on the blue line waiting for the
other team to come, and in the NHL you have to forecheck all the
time so that will be a big difference,'' Henrik said.
</P>
<P>
   For the cultural adjustment, the Canucks will rely on fellow
Swedes Markus Naslund and Mattias Ohlund.
</P>
<P>
   Up until this year, the Sedins lived with their parents in
Ornskoldsvik, a small mill-town about 360 miles North of Stockholm.
Naslund, who grew up in the same town, remembers struggling to
adjust to North American life when he first arrived in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've talked to them about pretty much everything. They had
questions and I've tried to answer the ones I could,'' said
Naslund, adding the lifestyle change is often harder than the
hockey. ''It's a big adjustment and for me it was the first time
really that I was that far away from home and living in a different
country and struggling a bit with the language.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, who coached Sweden's Peter Forsberg during his first
year in Quebec, isn't worried.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have the sense that these guys will become players whether
we do anything special with them or not,'' he said. ''They are
smart, intelligent kids and they are very driven. I think they'll
pick it up rather quickly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
