<HEADLINE> Qatar's Leader Meets Israel's Barak  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The leaders of Israel and Qatar met for
the first time Friday, despite dimming prospects for Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
   Qatar wanted to show that ''there are Arabs ready to extend
their hand to Israel if there is a just and fair peace with the
Arabs,'' Qatar's foreign minister, Sheikh Hamad Bin Jassem Bin
Jabor al-Thani, told his country's Al-Jazeera television.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has established tentative contacts with several Arab
states since its 1993 recognition of the Palestine Liberation
Organization. Qatar and Oman, two small Gulf nations, have
low-level ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's meeting on the sidelines of the U.N. Millennium
Summit, Qatar's leader, Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa al-Thani, urged
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak to reach an agreement with the
Palestinians, Qatar's foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
   The Qatari leader sided with the Palestinians in their dispute
with Israel over Jerusalem holy sites. ''All Muslim areas in east
Jerusalem should be returned'' to the Palestinians, the Qatari
foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's office said in a statement that the two countries
decided to develop fledgling relations. ''Qatar is an enthusiastic
supporter of the peace process, and hopes for its success,'' the
statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
