<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford extends truck plant shutdown for another week  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN HYDE
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) - Ford Motor Co. said Friday that it has extended
the shutdown of three truck factories by one week to divert 30,000
tires toward a massive recall.
</P>
<P>
   A longer shutdown is possible, Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   The tires are needed to fill replacement orders for 6.5 million
Firestone truck tires recalled in early August.
</P>
<P>
   The plants in St. Paul, Minn., Edison, N.J. and Hazelwood, Mo.,
have been closed for two weeks so that 15-inch tires used as
standard equipment on Ford Explorer/Mercury Mountaineer sport
utility vehicles and Ford Ranger pickups can be sent to Ford and
Lincoln/Mercury dealers.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the shutdown has freed up about 70,000 tires, but has
trimmed 15,000 Rangers and 10,000 Explorers/Mountaineers from
Ford's production. Ford said the additional week will cut another
8,500 Rangers and 5,400 Explorers from production. Not all the
vehicles would have used 15-inch tires.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are monitoring the situation week by week,'' Martin Inglis,
vice president of Ford North America, said in a statement. ''We are
seeing increased production from Goodyear, Michelin and other tire
makers and expect that to grow rapidly in the next week or two. The
safety and peace of mind of our customers remain our greatest
concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   The plants employ about 6,000 workers, who get paid during the
shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Firestone tires under recall - all P235/75R15-size ATX and
ATX II models, as well as Wilderness AT tires in the same size
built in Decatur, Ill., - have been linked to 88 deaths and at
least 250 injuries by federal investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, Ford said in a filing with the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission that it has agreed to bear some of the costs of
Firestone's recall. Ford did not give any additional details of the
cost-sharing arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials also said it is too soon to tell how Firestone's
tire recall and Ford's plant shutdowns will affect Ford earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The company said about 30 percent, or about 1.9 million, of the
6.5 million tires recalled have been replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has counted 63 personal injury lawsuits and 35 class action
lawsuits pending against the company related to the tire recall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
