<HEADLINE> Saul and Robert Steinberg sued by their mother for total $6.2 million </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Financier Saul Steinberg, chairman of the
diminished Reliance Group Holdings, and his brother Robert have
been sued by their mother for repayment of alleged debts totaling
$6.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Steinberg, 83, of Palm Beach, Fla., says in court papers
filed Thursday that Saul, 61, had failed to repay $4.7 million she
loaned him, and Robert 57, vice chairman of Reliance, had not
repaid a $1.5 million loan.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed in Manhattan's State Supreme Court, Mrs.
Steinberg said her sons signed agreements to repay her by Dec. 31,
1999. She said both have made periodic interest payments but
neither has paid any of the principal.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although our client would like to resolve this matter without
resort to litigation,'' Mrs. Steinberg's lawyer, Mitchell Hurley,
wrote Saul Steinberg in letter filed with the lawsuit, ''her less
formal appeals for payment so far have been unavailing.''
</P>
<P>
   In another letter to the sons' lawyer, Hurley denied that Mrs.
Steinberg arranged to have the debts forgiven upon her death. ''Ms.
Steinberg has made no such 'arrangements,''' Hurley wrote to Marvin
J. Goldstein, ''and intends to collect the money your clients owe
her in full.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Ms. Steinberg is in precarious financial condition due to the
recent troubles at Reliance,'' Hurley wrote in an Aug. 21 letter to
Goldstein. ''As you are undoubtedly aware, Ms. Steinberg's sole
sources of income are the Reliance dividend and interest payments
on the two notes.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Robert Steinberg missed two recently due interest
payments, Hurley wrote ''this has placed an even greater strain on
Ms. Steinberg's financial position.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliance is a New York casualty insurance and commercial
property holding company that has been the victim of falling prices
for both commodities.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which once tried to take over Walt Disney Co. and
Chemical Bank, recently said it might file for bankruptcy. At the
stock market's close Friday, Reliance was trading for less than 25
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Steinberg's promissory note is dated Oct. 1, 1996, and
his brother's is dated Jan. 1, 1997, court papers say. Saul
Steinberg's $4.7 million debt includes $2.1 million from a May 1985
promissory note. The interest rate on both notes in 5.51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Weiden, a spokesman for Reliance, said Saul Steinberg would
decline comment ''because it's a personal matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Steinberg could not be reached at his home in
Bernardsville, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-08-00 2104 </TRAILER>
