<HEADLINE> Teachers -- but not kids -- report to school amid teachers' strike  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Buffalo teachers reported to class Friday -
but their students didn't - as the teachers' illegal strike
continued to disrupt the new school year.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders asked the district's 3,800 teachers to go to work
for the day ''as a sign of good will'' following a pre-dawn
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But Superintendent Marion Canedo had already told students to
stay home because of uncertainty over the teachers' plans.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday afternoon, Buffalo Teachers Federation president
Philip Rumore told reporters that state mediator Adam Kaufman, from
the Public Employment Relations Board, had directed the sides to
bargain around-the-clock starting Saturday and to refrain from
speaking to the press.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Kaufman) also requested that, effective now, that there be a
complete news blackout, that neither side discuss anything that's
going on,'' Rumore said.
</P>
<P>
   School board spokesman Andrew Maddigan, however, said the board
had not agreed to any such blackout. The board met from 5 to 7:30
p.m. Friday to review research on the union's latest counteroffer
and the impact it would have on the district.
</P>
<P>
   Maddigan said the talks have shifted from each side submitting a
new offer to be digested by the other side. Instead, the ''subtle
nuances'' of some of the key issues are being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   The sides will meet Saturday at an undisclosed time and place,
Maddigan said. If school is to be closed again Monday, the district
will let parents know Sunday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're certainly optimistic (that there will be agreement,''
Maddigan said.
</P>
<P>
   With no students in class Friday, teachers spent the day
preparing lesson plans and their classrooms, said Rumore.
</P>
<P>
   The state mediator, meanwhile, went back and forth between union
and Board of Education negotiators discussing the union's latest
contract proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Rumore said the offer represented the union's ''bottom line''
and that teachers would not bend on their demand for pay raises of
3.5 percent in four out of five years.
</P>
<P>
   The district's latest offer contains across-the-board yearly
raises of 2 percent in three out of four years.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no way the teachers would accept less than the board
gave to everyone else,'' Rumore said, citing agreements with other
unions in the district. ''Why would we do that?''
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education scheduled a Friday evening meeting to
review the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully we'll be ready to make a response, if not tonight,
over the weekend,'' district spokesman Andrew Maddigan said.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers walked informational picket lines before heading
into school Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there's a teacher here who wouldn't rather be
inside teaching,'' said teacher Gordon Angevine. ''These are some
of the most dedicated professionals you're going to find. But
enough's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The strike violates the state's Taylor Law which forbids public
employees from striking. Teachers could face fines of two days' pay
for every day off the job.
</P>
<P>
   The union also face additional penalties for violating an order
issued Wednesday by state Supreme Court Justice Kevin Dillon
barring the union and four of its officers from engaging in a
strike or other illegal job actions.
</P>
<P>
   Rumore and the other union officers cited in the court order are
subject to jail terms of up to 30 days each and fines of up to
$1,000. A hearing is scheduled for Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said they were willing to negotiate through the
weekend and expressed hope that classes would resume Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're saying, as a token of good will, teachers are going to
report today.'' Rumore said Friday. ''Let's start today talking
about a settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said chances were ''so slim you can't see them'' that
teachers would return without a contract.
</P>
<P>
   The strike was called less than an hour before Thursday's start
of school, forcing the cancellation of what would have been the
second day of classes for 47,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of children and their parents were already headed to
school and work and parents were left scrambling to find child
care.
</P>
<P>
   In canceling Friday's classes, Canedo said she wanted to avoid
similar chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers' latest contract expired in June 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
