<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NY-BRF--Airline Held,0194  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WHITESTOWN, N.Y. (AP) - A financially struggling commuter
airline must continue to offer service in central New York to give
officials time to look for a replacement, a federal agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Transportation has ordered CommutAir to
remain at the Oneida County Airport until Oct. 19. DOT officials
said they will start looking for an airline to replace it.
</P>
<P>
   The air carrier, which operates as USAir Express, carried 8,200
passengers in 1999, 12,016 in 1998 and 13,272 in 1997. Three months
ago, it sought to discontinue its service to Oneida County Airport.
</P>
<P>
   CommutAir was not permitted to shut down its Oneida County
operations because the Utica area is classified as an essential air
service area, government officials said. The agency could issue
another order extending CommutAir's operation.
</P>
<P>
   If another company doesn't come forward in a reasonable time,
the DOT could offer to subsidize CommutAir's Oneida County service.
</P>
<P>
   CommutAir now offers four one-stop round trips to Newark each
weekday and some one-stop round trips each weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
