<HEADLINE> Seahawks' Kitna Seen Playing Sunday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) -- Seattle Seahawks quarterback Jon Kitna
practiced Friday, one day after having sore ribs, and was expected
to play Sunday against the St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna left Thursday afternoon's practice because of discomfort
on his left side, and his status for the game was unclear. But he
said he was pain-free Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it will be an issue at all on Sunday,'' Kitna
said.
</P>
<P>
   The injury was the latest turn in an ongoing quarterback
controversy for the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, coach Mike Holmgren gave Kitna the starting
nod after he was pulled in the third quarter of a 23-0 loss to the
Miami Dolphins in the season opener. Second-year player Brock
Huard, whose only NFL experience came in last Sunday's game, is
Kitna's backup.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren said rookie wide receiver Darrell Jackson will replace
Derrick Mayes in the starting lineup Sunday, while Mack Strong will
replace Reggie Brown at fullback.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Christian Fauria practiced Friday and is expected to
play against St. Louis, although Itula Mili will start.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie tackle Chris McIntosh, who was a roster exemption because
he missed all of training camp in a contract dispute, was activated
for Sunday's game. Holmgren said veteran Todd Weiner will start at
right tackle, but McIntosh is also scheduled to play.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game has been blacked out locally because it did not
sell out by Friday afternoon's deadline. About 4,000 tickets remain
at the 68,000-seat Husky Stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
