<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio campaigns for death tax repeal, Clinton trumpets education  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT VERNON, N.Y. (AP) - Senate rivals Rick Lazio and Hillary
Clinton stuck to familiar campaign topics Friday: He in the
suburbs, urging the repeal of the estate tax, and she in New York
City, reciting education themes.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're either for the elimination or you're against the
elimination of the death tax, I think it comes down to that,''
Lazio said after visiting Blakely's Tree Company, a family owned
business in Westchester County. He later visited the Rockland
Bakery in Nanuet, a business run by five brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was part of an unsuccessful Republican-led effort to
override President Clinton's veto of a bill to abolish inheritance
taxes. The House fell 14 votes short Thursday of the necessary
two-thirds margin to override the veto with 431 members voting.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said the 10-year, $105 billion repeal bill was
''a huge tax cut for the most well-off Americans'' that threatened
the nation's economic health and critical government programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The travesty of it is that the death tax, by forcing people to
pay this tax simply because people die and forcing people to sell
their assets overnight, it devalues the economy, it undermines our
tax base, it undermines our employment base and it's wrong and it's
bad,'' Lazio said. ''I'm disappointed that both the president
vetoed it and that Mrs. Clinton supports the veto.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said, ''Hillary
believes we should pass a responsible and targeted tax cut for the
estate tax, that gives real benefits more immediately to small
businesses and family farms.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also criticized the president for his impromptu handshake
with Cuban President Fidel Castro at the United Nations Millennium
Summit this week.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would not have shook Fidel Castro's hand,'' he said. ''I
think he stands for oppression, for lack of freedom. He is
undemocratic, I think he has been terrible on human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio then alluded to his opponent's notorious embrace last year
of the wife of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat while visiting the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what there is to shake his hand about to tell you
the truth,'' Lazio said ''I think we send the wrong message when we
embrace, whether its Mrs. Arafat or Fidel Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't comment on the handshake, saying, ''You'll have
to ask the president and the White House about that.''
</P>
<P>
   On her visits to elementary schools in Brooklyn and Staten
Island, Clinton was grilled by students and met with teachers to
discuss their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Brooklyn's P.S. 169, an overcrowded 85-year-old school
that still has a coal burning furnace, Clinton hammered Lazio on
his educational record saying, ''when it comes to standing up for
the children of New York he's been missing in action.''
</P>
<P>
   She criticized him for opposing bills that would add 100,000
federally funded teaching spots and give New York $2.4 billion in
federal funds for school construction and repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been saying for more than a year that I want to fight for
New York state's fair share. Well, one of the places that we could
get more of our fair share is in school construction funding and in
new teachers, both of which he opposed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also visited P.S. 36 in the Annadale section of Staten
Island, a school that suffered millions of dollars in damage after
allegedly being torched by several teens earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The 9-year-olds in Judy O'Donnell's fourth-grade class cheered
when Clinton told them her favorite American League team was the
New York Yankees and she scored points with Rubinnis Gutierrez, a
10-year-old fifth-grader in Sunset Park when she declared her
support for recess.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said a college student told her some schools are trying
to cut out recess and physical education classes. ''I not only want
you to have good things inside your head but I want you to be
strong and have fun, too,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank you, thank you,'' gushed the dimple-cheeked Gutierrez.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, Clinton joined her husband and five Democratic
senators at a dinner that raised about $615,000 for the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee. Silicon Alley executives paid
$25,000 each to attend. Clinton promised to work to improve
education so Internet companies will be able to hire qualified
workers in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Touching on an issue important to the dot-com community, she
said that as a short-term solution, she would seek visas so
qualified foreign workers can enter the country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also admitted apprehension about her first debate with
Lazio next Wednesday because she has never debated. She joked that
anyone who has ever covered her knows ''how hard it is for me to
say anything in 90 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also was asked about the debate, and although he has
experience in debates while running for his House seat, ''to be
fair ... this is a different league and I think everybody
understands that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-08-00 2146 </TRAILER>
