<DOCNO> APW20000908.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teachers Go to Class Amid Strike  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- An arbiter Friday directed the school board
and its striking teachers to begin marathon negotiations to resolve
an empasse that has cancelled classes for two days.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, teachers reported to class, but the 47,000 students did
not. The district had cancelled classes to avoid the chaos caused
Thursday when teachers started the strike in the early morning as
students were heading to school.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Teachers Federation president Philip Rumore said Friday
afternoon that a state mediator had directed both sides to bargain
around the clock starting Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   School board spokesman Andrew Maddigan, said the board met late
Friday afternoon to review the union's latest offer. He said the
board would have a response by Friday evening or the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're certainly optimistic,'' Maddigan said.
</P>
<P>
   With no students in class Friday, teachers devoted their time to
preparing lesson plans and their classrooms, Rumore said. In a
pre-dawn meeting, union leaders had asked the district's 3,800
teachers to go to work for the day ''as a sign of good will.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there's a teacher here who wouldn't rather be
inside teaching,'' said teacher Gordon Angevine, who marched in a
picket line Friday before entering school. ''These are some of the
most dedicated professionals you're going to find. But enough's
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   If school is to be closed again Monday, the district will let
parents know Sunday, Maddigan said.
</P>
<P>
   The district's latest offer contains across-the-board yearly
raises of 2 percent in three out of four years. Rumore said that
teachers would not bend on their demand for pay raises of 3.5
percent in four out of five years. The teachers' latest contract
expired in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The strike violates the state's Taylor Law which forbids public
employees from striking, and teachers could face fines of two days'
pay for every day off the job.
</P>
<P>
   The union could face additional penalties for violating a
judge's order barring the union and four of its officers from
engaging in a strike or other illegal job actions. A hearing is
scheduled for Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-08-00 2146 </TRAILER>
