<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four more sentenced in $35 million shoplifting operation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UTICA, N.Y. (AP) - Four more members of a Utica-based
shoplifting and fencing ring that stole millions of dollars worth
of goods from upstate New York retail outlets were sentenced
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Frank L. Ferraro, 58, received three to nine years in state
prison and Carl J. Mazza, 56, one to three years on their
convictions for enterprise corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Zogby, 75, was convicted of fourth-degree criminal
possession of stolen property and was sentenced to nine months in
county jail and fined $5,000. Tammy Smith, 41, was also convicted
of criminal possession of stolen property and got six months in
county jail and five years' probation.
</P>
<P>
   That makes 27 - out of 28- defendants sentenced in connection
with the shoplifting ring that operated in 11 central New York
counties and stole more than $35 million in merchandise over eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests were made in February.
</P>
<P>
   The ring worked in teams and targeted specific items that were
believed to be easy to resell, including videos, razor blades,
batteries, compact discs, video games, Texas calculators,
over-the-counter medications, film, disposable cameras, electric
razors, tools, compact radios and CD players.
</P>
</TEXT>
