<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Killed in Atlantic City Ambush  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- A man with an assault rifle opened
fire on a car stopped at a traffic light Friday, killing three of
the four people inside, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   At least 24 shots were fired in the pre-dawn ambush on U.S. 30,
about two miles west of Atlantic City's Boardwalk casinos,
according to prosecutor Jeffrey Blitz.
</P>
<P>
   The victims probably knew the killer, who remained at large late
Friday, Blitz said.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman began on the driver's side and then walked around the
car, firing through the windows and killing the two passengers on
the right side of the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   One victim tried to flee but was shot to death as he ran down
the highway.
</P>
<P>
   The survivor, who was sitting in the left rear seat, was injured
by flying glass but was not shot, Blitz said. He was cooperating
with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Blitz declined to provide further details, but he ruled out road
rage as a motive. ''I have a particular interest that the suspect
or suspects not read about it until I'm prepared to make an
arrest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were identified as Lamont Wilson, 21, Richard White,
26, and Michael Demps, 20, all of Pleasantville, N.J. The fourth
man wasn't identified by authorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
