<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Apologizes to N. Korea  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The State Department has apologized to North
Korea for the forced search of that country's U.N. delegation
members en route to the U.N. Millennium Summit, saying it did not
reflect U.S. policy, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The search in Frankfurt, Germany, was part of a security check
as the delegation led by Kim Yong Nam, head of the communist
country's parliament, was transferring to an American Airlines
flight for New York.
</P>
<P>
   He was to have met with South Korean President Kim Dae-jung two
months after a historic summit meeting in Pyongyang with North
Korea's paramount leader, Kim Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration approves of the thaw and has been
stepping up its contacts with North Korea, even while keeping it
ineligible for all but humanitarian aid as a supporter of terrorism
and dismissing any suggestion of withdrawing some of the U.S.
troops who have guarded South Korea for a half-century.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea filed a formal protest against the United States
last Friday after the Frankfurt search, calling the incident
humiliating, and the delegation called off its trip to the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Yong Nam would have been the highest-ranking North Korean
official to attend a U.N. meeting since the two Koreas joined the
United Nations in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation members claimed the search was ordered by U.S.
security officials, and North Korea's vice foreign minister, Choe
Su Hon, told reporters at a news conference at Frankfurt airport
that North Korea had demanded an apology from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a rude and provocative act,'' Choe said.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines issued a statement Tuesday apologizing for the
search, but denied that the diplomats were asked to strip. No U.S.
government agencies participated in the search, the airline said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Albright said the United States sent a message of
regret to the North Korean government, and ''they expressed
understanding this is not a position of the U.S. government.''
</P>
<P>
   She said North Korea would send a high-level delegation to New
York next week for the special session of the U.N. General
Assembly. She is expected to meet with its head.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will put this behind us,'' she said. ''What happened in
Frankfurt is unfortunate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
