<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton says first lady put her career on hold for him  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - President Clinton, helping raise money for
Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate campaign, said Friday night he has
felt guilty for 25 years that his wife had to put her career on
hold while he ran for office.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of all the things that her adversaries sometimes say, the
thing that steams me the most is that she wouldn't be doing this if
she weren't the first lady,'' Clinton said. ''But I want you to
know if she weren't the first lady, she'd have been in a position
to do this 25 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke at a $25,000-a-person fund-raiser that was
expected to net $615,000 for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, which is helping pay for this wife's campaign. He spoke
after attending a U.N. summit that attracted 160 world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Praising his wife, Clinton said, ''When we first met and fell in
love, I actually felt guilty about it because I thought I was
robbing her of the career that I thought she should have.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought she was better organized than me,'' he said. ''I
thought she understood things about public policy I didn't know. I
thought she had more talent as a public servant that anybody I ever
met.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
