<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-08 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Drugs Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   A British cyclist who tested positive for drugs was
barred from
racing for a year Friday, while a Canadian equestrian team member
was banned for life for cocaine use and another Olympian from
Canada lost her appeal of a positive steroid test.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Problems with athlete drug use continued to pop up in the final
days before the Sydney Olympics as a White House-financed study on
drug testing was released in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The study recommended establishing an agency independent of the
International Olympic Committee to take on the task of drug testing
and determining which substances to ban.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Canadian Equestrian Federation banned Eric Lamaze
from competition for life because he tested positive for cocaine
for the second time.
</P>
<P>
   Lamaze, the 1995 Canadian show-jumping champion, was kicked off
the Olympic team when he tested positive Aug. 29. He asked that his
urine sample be retested, but the results of that test Thursday at
an accredited IOC lab also came up positive.
</P>
<P>
   Lamaze was to compete in the team and individual jumping events
in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a sad day for all of us,'' federation executive director
Don Adams said. ''We are very sorry for what this means for Eric,
who was an outstanding athlete at the peak of his career.''
</P>
<P>
   A doping review panel from the Canadian Center for Ethics also
upheld the suspension of hammer thrower Robin Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons, the Canadian national champion, tested positive for
norandrosterone, a metabolite of nandrolone, at the Olympic trials
in August.
</P>
<P>
   She can still appeal to an independent arbitrator who could rule
by the end of next week. Lyons, 23, of Edmonton, has denied taking
steroids.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not Ben Johnson,'' she said this week, referring to the
Canadian sprinter stripped of his gold medal in the 100 meters at
the Seoul Olympics after testing positive for steroids.
</P>
<P>
   In England, British cyclist Neil Campbell was found guilty of a
drug offense and banned from competition for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, 26, was included on the Olympic squad but had not been
selected for Britain's final team. Two tests showed Campbell had
higher concentrations of human chorionic gonadotrophin (HCG) than
permitted.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell was asked to account for the findings at a disciplinary
hearing Friday, after which he was found guilty of breaking British
Cycling Federation and international anti-doping rules.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the National Center on Addiction and Substance
Abuse (CASA) at Columbia University released a report that said
heavy corporate endorsement of the Olympics combined with the lack
of an effective drug policing system ''create an environment that
encourages doing anything -- including doping -- to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Anti-Doping Agency is run by Dick Pound, an IOC vice
president. The IOC set up the agency to coordinate a global system
of no-notice, out-of-competition testing, but the study said an
independent agency could do a better job.
</P>
<P>
   Pound, at Olympic meetings in Sydney, said no one connected with
the study had contacted either the IOC or the anti-doping agency
for comments or explanation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-08-00 2227 </TRAILER>
