<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Galveston Marks Deadly Storm  </HEADLINE>
By MARK BABINECK
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas (AP) -- The Sisters of Charity orphanage sat in
an idyllic location -- 93 boys and girls lived just a few strides
from Galveston Island's dunes and the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A century ago Friday, the gulf ambushed the orphanage and the
city beyond. Ninety children and 10 nuns were among the 6,000 to
10,000 people who died when a surprise hurricane barreled ashore --
the nation's deadliest disaster.
</P>
<P>
   A day filled with solemn remembrances of the Great Storm began
Friday with a wreath-laying ceremony at the site of St. Mary's
Orphanage, now marked by a 17-foot sea wall that has protected
Galveston from the gulf's fury ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Murney's father was 13 when the hurricane flooded
Galveston on Sept. 8, 1900, and tore the orphanage apart, hurling
the boy into a tree.
</P>
<P>
   ''He especially recalled holding on to his younger brother,''
said Murney, 75, of Springfield, Mo. ''The roof collapsed and he
was hit on the hand by a timber. He had that scar on his hand all
of his life. He lost his brother, and never saw him again.''
</P>
<P>
   In a half-hour ceremony, 100 flowers -- 10 roses for the nuns,
other flowers for the children -- were laid at the historical
monument along the seawall. Members of the Sisters of Charity of
the Incarnate Word sang ''Queen of the Waves,'' the hymn their
predecessors had sung to calm the children a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   At a memorial service Friday night, prayers honored those who
didn't survive and praise for those who did. A 1,200-seat school
auditorium was packed with an overflow crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ''Galveston didn't have to come back,'' said Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison, a Galveston native. ''Who would have blamed Galveston
for saying, 'We tried, but it wasn't meant to be'?''
</P>
<P>
   Galveston in 1900 was the state's fourth-largest city, an gulf
port awash in wealth. Few took storms seriously.
</P>
<P>
   On a cloudy Saturday, rain turned into tidal floods and wind
accelerated to damaging levels. By midafternoon, the 3-mile-wide
island was battered by waves that tore apart structures near the
beach.
</P>
<P>
   Around nightfall, the 15-foot storm surge moved ashore.
Inhabitants either went down with their homes or were ejected into
the torrent to fend for themselves. When the water subsided around
midnight, a wall of debris two stories high remained.
</P>
<P>
   While about one-sixth of the town's 38,000 residents perished,
the city refused to die. Man-made defenses such as the seawall have
held firm in hurricanes since.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, those who died will be commemorated by a 10-foot
bronze statue built at the seawall. It shows a man, a woman and a
child looking toward the islands.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.1900storm.com/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.galveston.com/islebeat/gchm.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
