<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAdrian P. Burke:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Adrian P. Burke, a former New York Court of
Appeals judge who counted former Gov. Mario Cuomo among his clerks,
died Sunday. He was 95.
</P>
<P>
   Burke was a judge on New York's highest court from 1955 to 1973.
His law clerks included Cuomo and Fabian Palomino, who later served
as special counsel to the Democratic governor.
</P>
<P>
   In his last opinion for the court, Burke wrote for the 4-3
majority that the wife of an Attica state prison employee should be
allowed to sue the state for her husband's death during the
retaking of the prison following the 1971 inmate riot.
</P>
<P>
   The state, claiming sovereign immunity, had argued that it
wasn't liable for the death of the accounting clerk who had been
taken hostage by inmates and then was shot to death by state
troopers retaking the prison.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the ruling, the clerk's wife was able to
establish that the state used excessive force and was awarded
damages for her husband's death.
Madeline Colliflower:
</P>
<P>
   HAYS, Mont. (AP) -- Madeline Colliflower, an American Indian
activist whose arrest for disobeying a tribal court order in 1963
spawned the Indian Civil Rights Act, died Thursday. She was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Colliflower, whose Indian name was Si-Siya, was one of the last
full-blooded members of the Gros Ventre tribe.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, she was convicted for disobeying a tribal court order
to remove her cattle from land leased to another person.
</P>
<P>
   She sued, arguing her constitutional right to due process was
violated because the tribal judge also acted as prosecutor and
convicted her without allowing her to present any evidence or
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge W.J. Jameson originally declined to hear the
case, citing a lack of jurisdiction, but later ruled that
Colliflower's rights were violated.
</P>
<P>
   The decision led to the Indian Civil Rights Act of 1968, which,
among other things, guarantees defendants in tribal court the same
rights provided in the U.S. Constitution.
Robert Dewar:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Robert Dewar, who was responsible for changing
the name of S.S. Kresge to Kmart Corp. in 1977, died Thursday of
complications from colon cancer. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   Dewar began his Kmart career in 1949 when the store was called
S.S. Kresge. As a lawyer, he started in the retailer's legal
department. Dewar eventually became president and chief
administrative officer in 1970. In 1972, he was appointed chairman
and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Under Dewar's leadership, the Troy-based retail chain went
through a massive expansion. In 1971, the company opened 271 Kmart
stores -- a record single-year store launch for any retailer at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   He retired in 1988.
George Lazarus:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- George Lazarus, a widely known marketing
journalist and daily business columnist for the Chicago Tribune
since 1972, died Friday. He was 68.
</P>
<P>
   Lazarus wrote a marketing column in Chicago for nearly 40 years
-- for Chicago Today, the Chicago Daily News and then the Tribune.
He also wrote for Adweek's Marketing Week and the New York Daily
News and was a business commentator on WGN, CLTV, WMAQ, WLAK and
WFLD-TV.
</P>
<P>
   His columns carried considerable influence among Chicago's
business, advertising and marketing executives.
</P>
<P>
   He was chosen recently for The All-Star Newspaper, an online
selection of offerings by top newspaper writers as selected by
Brill's Content.
Leonard J. Seyberth:
</P>
<P>
   EAU CLAIRE, Wis. (AP) -- Leonard J. Seyberth, credited with
developing the party permit system for deer hunting, died Aug. 31.
He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Seyberth served on the Wisconsin Conservation Commission, which
sought better ways of managing the deer herd, especially by
allowing hunters to kill does rather than the traditional bucks
only.
</P>
<P>
   Before the commission was created in 1953, there were
anterless-deer-only seasons and either-sex seasons. Under the party
permit system, a group of four hunters applied for an either-sex
deer permit. If successful, they received one permit.
</P>
<P>
   The system went into effect in 1956 and went on to be copied by
wildlife management agencies in many states.
Curt Siodmak:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Curt Siodmak, who wrote the science fiction
novel ''Donovan's Brain'' and created ''The Wolf Man'' for
Universal Pictures, died on Sept. 2 of heart failure. He was 98.
</P>
<P>
   He was the writer or co-writer of more than 70 screenplays
between 1928 and 1979, including ''Her Jungle Love'' with Dorothy
Lamour in 1938 and ''The Invisible Man Returns'' with Vincent Price
in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   A series of ''Invisible Man'' pictures followed. His credits
also included ''The Wolf Man'' (1941), ''Frankenstein Meets the
Wolf Man'' (1943), ''Son of Dracula'' (1943), ''I Walked with a
Zombie'' (1943), ''The Beast with Five Fingers'' (1946) and ''Love
Slaves of the Amazon'' (1957).
</P>
<P>
   His cult novel ''Donovan's Brain,'' first published in 1943, has
never been out of print. Siodmak's autobiography, ''Wolf Man's
Maker: Memoir of a Hollywood Writer,'' will be published by
Scarecrow Press in November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
